(171, 'Sodium Ironedetate', 'Iron deficiency either due to chronic blood loss or poor absorption.', 'Iron intolerance.', 'History peptic ulcer, severe renal failure. Iron and tetracycline bind together leading to impairment of absorption.', 'GI upset, black stools, abdominal discomfort or pain by oral therapy.'),
(172, 'Venlafaxine', 'Depression. Generalized anxiety disorder. Social anxiety disorder. Panic disorder.', 'Hypersensitivity. Concomitant use in patients taking monoamine oxidase inhibitors (MAOIs). Uncontrolled hypertension. Serious ventricular arrhythmia. Lactation.', 'Moderate to severe renal or hepatic impairment. MI, bleeding disorder, epilepsy, hypomania or mania. Raised intraocular pressure or risk at angle-closure glaucoma. May impair performance of skilled tasks.', 'Nausea, vomiting, anorexia, dry mouth, constipation, orthostatic hypotension, tremour, sweating, rash, anxiety, dizziness, fatigue, headache, syncope, insomnia, somnolence, constipation, hyponatraemia, sexual dysfunction, dyspepsia, visual disturbances, mydriasis, increased cholesterol concentrations, increased LFT. Aggressive behavior (especially at the start and when stopping therapy). Blood dyscrasias, Stevens-Johnson syndrome, hepatitis.'),
(173, 'Calcium Folinate', 'Antidote for methotrexate and folic acid antagonists.', 'Pernicious anaemia and megaloblastic anaemia secondary to the lack of Vit B12.', 'Undiagnosed megaloblastic anaemia, folate dependent tumors.', 'Nausea, pyrexia, vomiting, urticaria, anaphylactic reactions.'),
(174, 'Insulin (Human)', 'Produced by Recombinant technology or, enzymatic modification of procaine insulin. Insulin analogues. Type I DM. Type II DM not controlled by oral drugs. Diabetic ketoacidosis (Diabetic coma). Hyperosmolar (nonketotic hyperglycaemic coma). During septecemia or surgical procedures.', 'Hypersensitivity. Hypoglycaemia and insulinoma.', 'Renal impairment. Ischemic heart disease. Combination therapy. Insulin resistance.', 'Hypoglycaemia, development of antibodies to insulin, hypersensitivity, local Lipodystrophy (very rare), Oedema. Local reaction at injection site.'),
(175, 'Tinidazole', 'Amoebiasis. Trichomoniasis and giardiasis. Anaerobic infection. Bacterial vaginosis. Eradication of H.pylori associated with peptic ulcer disease. Acute necrotising ulcerative gingivitis.', 'Hypersensitivity. Blood dyscrasias. Neurological disorder. Porphyria. First trimester of pregnancy and lactation.', 'Second and third trimester of pregnancy. Anticoagulants. Alcoholism.', 'Matallic taste, nausea, vomiting and headache. Furred tongue. GI discomfort. Dark urine. Neuropathy and seizures. Urticaria. Leucopenia. Angioedema.'),
(176, 'Streptomycin Sulphate', 'Plaque, tuberculosis, tularaemia, sub acute bacterial endocarditis, meningitis, brucellosis. Mycobacterium avium complex infections.', 'Hypersensitivity. Pregnancy. Severe renal damage.', 'Renal impairment. Lactation and premature infants.', 'Giddiness, vertigo, tinnitus, ataxia, hypersensitivity reactions, ototoxicity and nephrotoxicity. Aplastic anaemia and agranulocytosis.'),
(177, 'Hydroxy Progesterone Hexanoate', 'As contraceptive. Hormone replacement therapy (HRT). Dysfunctional uterine bleeding. Endrometriosis. Premenstrual syndrome/tension. Threatened/habitual abortion. Endometrial carcinoma. Dysmenorrhea. Suppression of postpartum lactation. Hypoventilation.', 'Hypersensitivity.Undiagnosed vaginal bleeding, breast cancer, pregnancy, lactation. Thromboembolic disorders. History of seizures. Markedly impaired liver functions.', 'Diabetes. Exclude pregnancy. Suspicion of thromboembolic disorders.', 'Breast engorgement, headache, rise in body temperature, edema, esophageal reflux, acne and mood swings may occur. Irregular bleeding or amenorrhoea. Long term use of progestin in HRT may increase the risk of breast cancer. Blood sugar may rise and diabetes may be precipitated by long-term use of potent agents like levonorgestrel. Given in early pregnancy, progestins can cause masculinization of female foetus and other congenital abnormalities.'),
(178, 'Sulphamethoxy Pyridazine', 'Prophylaxis of rheumatic fever. Bullous pemphigoid. Skin infections. Pneumocystis carinii pneumonia. Trachoma. Staphylo Coccal infections.', 'Hypersensitivity.', 'Hybration should be adequate.', 'GI upset. Anaphylaxis. Skin rashes. Neutropenia. Thrombocytopenia. Crystalluria.'),
(179, 'Clemastine Fumarate', 'Hay fever and other allergic rhinopathies, urticaria, pruritus, itching dermatoses as adjuvant in acute and chronic eczema, contact dermatitis, drug eruptions, insect stings and bites.', 'Hypersensitivity, narrow-angle glaucoma, pyloroduodenal obstruction, stenosing peptic ulcer, prostatic hypertrophy with urinary retention or bladder neck obstruction. Contraindicated during pregnancy and lactation. Contraindicated below the age of one year.', 'Glaucoma, tasks requiring mental alertness, sedatives, tranquilizers, chronic hepatic/renal dysfunction.', 'Fatique, sedation, occationally CNS stimulation particularly in children, dry mouth, headache, dizziness, skin rash, nausea, gastralgia, constipation.'),
(180, 'Chloramphenicol Sodium Succinate', 'Enteric fever (Typhoid and Para typhoid). H.Influenzae meningitis. Anaerobic infections, intraocular infections, urinary tract infections, conjunctivitis, external ear infections. Corneal ulcer, bacterial conjunctivitis, trachoma, ocular infections. Otitis externa, chronic otitis media. Pre and post antral or mastoid surgery.', 'Hypersensitivity, trivial infections or prophylaxis, concomitant use of penicillins. Large doses in neonates, bone marrow hypoplasia. Contraindicated during pregnancy and lactation.', 'Never use in minor infections or those of undefined etiology. Avoid repeated courses. Concomitant use of anti coagulants, and convulsants, sulphonylurea. Hazard of aplastic anaemia is very unlikely but should be borne in mind while assessing the benefit expected from their use. Application should be discontinued if allergic reaction occurs.', 'GI upsets, optic and peripheral neurites, dry mouth, allergic skin reactions. Gray baby syndrome, supra infections. Bone marrow depression, aplastic anaemia, agranulocytosis, thrombocytopenia or pancytopenia. Hypersensitivity reactions, irritation.'),
(181, 'Imipenem', 'Imipenem is always available in combination with Cilastatin. It is an extremely potent against broad-spectrum beta-lactam antibiotic whose range of activity includes gram positive cocci, Enterobacteriaceae, Ps aeruginosa, Listeria as well as anaerobes like Bact.fragilis and Cl. difficile. It is also effective in a wide range of serious hospital acquired infections including those in neutropenic, cancer and AIDS patients.', 'Hypersensitivity.', 'Potential risk to the foetus. CNS disorders such as epilepsy, renal, hepatic impairment. Pregnancy and lactation. In patients having history of convulsions, the drug should not be started before starting anti-convulsant therapy.', 'Skin rashes, urticaria, eosinophilia, fever, nausea, vomiting, diarrhoea, tooth or tongue discoloration and altered taste. It induce seizures at higher doses.'),
(182, 'Gemfibrozil', 'Hyperlipidaemia, lipoprotein abnormalities resistant to diet alone.', 'Children, pregnancy and lactation, severe impairment of renal and hepatic functions. Alcoholism, gallbladder disease. Hypersensitivity.', 'Causes of secondary hyperlipidaemia such as hypothyroidism and diabetes must be treated before initiating therapy. Renal impairment, blood disorders. Regular ophthalamic check up required. May increase risk of cholelithiasis.', 'Myositic syndrome, cholelithiasis, GI disturbances, rash, headache, blood dyscrasias, myalgia. Impotence, painful extremities, blurred vision, pruritus, urticaria, impotence, dizziness, cholestatic jaundice. Bone marrow hypoplasia, intracranial haemorrhage, nephrotoxicity, peripheral neuritis.'),
(183, 'Dehydroemetine', 'Intestinal amoebiasis hepatic amoebiasis and other systemic disease due to E.histolytica.', 'Cardiac or renal disease. Contraindicated during pregnancy.', 'Emetine therapy last 45 days.', 'Nausea, vomiting, diarrhoea, weakness, myalgia, hypotension, cardiac dysrhythmia.'),
(184, 'Methocarbamol', 'Adjunct in the short term symtomastic treatment of muscle spasm.', 'Hypersensitivity, coma, known brain damage, epilepsy, myasthenia gravis, renal impairment.. Pregnancy, lactation and children below the age of twelve years.', 'Hepatic disorder, acidosis.', 'Headache, anorexia, nausea, vertigo, fever, skin eruptions, drowsiness, blurred vision, convulsions, metallic taste, incoordination, diplopia, nystagmus.'),
(185, 'Granisetron', 'Nausea and vomiting induced by cytotoxic chemotherapy and radiotherapy. Prophylaxis and treatment of postoperative nausea and vomiting.', 'Hypersensitivity. Contraindicated below the age of two years.', 'Subacute intestinal obstruction or ileus. Moderate to severe hepatic impairment. Congenital long QT syndrome or other risk factors for QT prolongation. Pregnancy and lactation.', 'Anxiety, fever, headache, asthenia, somnolence, dizziness, insomnia. Elevation of liver enzymes (AST & ALT). Constipation, hypersensitivity reactions, chest pain, CV disturbances, visual disturbances, development of seizures, extrapyramidal reactions.'),
(186, 'Adenosine', 'Treatment of paroxysmal supraventricular tachycardia. Diagnosis of re-entrant atrial and ventricular tachycardia.', 'Second or third degree AV block, sick sinus syndrome, Bronchial asthma.', 'Patient with atrial fibrillation/flutter and an accessory bypass tract may develop increased conduction down the anomalous pathway.', 'Facial flush, dyspnoea, nausea and light headache occur commonly. Rarely sweating, palpitations, heaviness in arms.'),
(187, 'Atorvastatin', 'Primary hypercholesterolaemia, heterozygous familial hypercholesterolaemia, homozygous familial hypercholesterolaemia or combined hyperlipidaemia.', 'Hypersensitivity. Active liver disease. Pregnancy and lactation. Porphyria.', 'Alcoholism. Risk factors for myopathy or rhabdomyolysis. Hypothyroidism.', 'GI disturbances. Reversible myositis, headache, insomnia, anorexia, impotence, chest pain. Xerostomia, angioedema, myalgia, rash/pruritus, alopecia, allergy, infection. Thrombocytopenia. Rhabdomyolysis with acute renal failure.'),
(188, 'Rabeprazole', 'Benign gastric and peptic ulcer. Erosive of ulcerative gastro-oesophageal reflux disease (GORD). Acid peptic disease.', 'Hypersensitivity. Pregnancy and lactation.', 'Hepatic impairment. Gastric or oesophageal malignancy should be excluded.', 'Headache, diarrhoea and nausea, rhinitis, abdominal pain, asthenia, flatulence, pharyngitis vomiting non-specific pain-back pain, dizziness, flu syndrome, infection, cough constipation and insomnia.'),
(189, 'Anastrozole', 'Adjuvant treatment of oestrogen-receptor positive early invasive breast cancer in postmenopausal women; adjuvant treatment of oestrogen receptor positive early breast cancer in postmenopausal women following 2-3 years of tamoxifen therapy; advanced breast cancer.', 'Contraindicated during pregnancy and lactation.; moderate or severe hepatic disease; moderate or severe renal impairment; not for premenopausal women.', 'Estrogens containing therapies should not be used with anastrozole as they may diminish its pharmacological action. Tamoxifen should not be co-administered with anastrozole.', 'Hot flushes, vaginal dryness, vaginal bleeding, hair thinning, anorexia, nausea, vomiting, diarrhoea, headache, arthralgia, bone fractures, rash (including stevens-johnson syndrome). Asthenia and drowsiness may initially affect ability to drive or operate machinery.'),
(190, 'Quinine', 'Malaria: a) Uncomplicated resistant faciparum malaria. b) Complicated and severe malaria including cerebral malaria. Nocturnal muscle cramps. Varicose.', 'Hypersensitivity, haemolytic anaemia, quinine-resistant falciparum infection. Pregnancy, lactation. Tinnitus or optic neuritis. Myasthenia gravis. Prolonged QT interval.', 'Arterial fibrillation. Renal or hepatic impairment. CV diseases. G6PD deficiency. Diabetes mellitus.', 'Tinnitus. Impaired hearing, headache, blurred vision, vomiting, diarrhoea, abdominal pain, vertigo. Urticaria, pruritus, fever, angioedema, asthma, dyspnoea, haemoglobinuria, thrombocytopenic purpura, hypolgycaemia, renal failure, hypoprothrombinaemia, agranulocytosis.'),
(191, 'Tenoxicam', 'Osteoarthritis, rheumatoid arthritis, ankylosing spondylitis, gout, non articular rheumatic disorders.', 'Hypersensitivity. Active peptic ulceration. GI bleeding. Severe gastritis. Pregnancy, lactation and children. Haemorrhagic diathesis. Asthma.', 'Renal/hepatic/cardiovascular diseases. Fluid retention, inflammatory bowel disease. Elderly.', 'Dyspepsia, nausea, abdominal pain, constipation, diarrhoea, flatulence, indigestion, oedema, headache, rashes, blood dyscrasias. Visual disturbances. Raised liver enzymes. Sleep disturbances, thrombotic events, nephrotoxicity, hepatotoxicity, toxic epidermal necrolysis.'),
(192, 'Hydrocortisone Acetate', 'Atopic eczema. Allergic contact dermatitis. Lichen simplex. Primary irritant dermatitis. Seborrheic dermatitis. Psoriasis of face, flexures. Varicose eczema. Cystic acne. Alopecia areata. Discoid LE. Hypertrophied scars, keloids. Lichen planus. Nail disorders. Psoriasis of palm, sole, elbow, knee. A combination of steroid with proper antibiotic cover may also be used for: Impetigo, furunculosis, secondary infected dermatoses, napkin rash, otitis externa, intertriginous eruptions.', 'Hypersensitivity. Rosacea or perioral dermatitis. Primary infective skin. Pregnancy and lactation.', 'Infants. Secondary dermatological infections.', 'Thinning of epidermis. Dermal changes - atrophy. Telangiectasia, Striae. Easy bruising, Hypopigmentation. Delayed wound healing. Fungal and bacterial infections. Systemic adverse effects of topical steroids on prolong use: Adrenal pituitary suppression. Cushings syndrome.'),
(193, 'Donepezil', 'Alzheimers disease speciality for mild to moderate disease severity.', 'Hypersensitivity. Severe hepatic and renal impairment. Contraindicated during pregnancy and lactation', 'Mechanical intestinal obstruction or peritonitis. Recent intestinal or bladder surgery, bronchial asthma or COPD, arrhythmias, bradycardia, recent MI and hypotention, vagotonia, epilepsy, hyperthyroidism, parkinsonism, moderate renal or hepatic impairmemt or peptic ulcer. Sick sinus syndrome or other supraventricular conduction abnormalities. May exacerbate extrapyramidal symptoms.', 'Nausea, vomiting, diarrhoea. Fatique, isomonia, muscle cramps. Occasionally headache, dizziness, syncope, bradycradia (rarely SA block), AV Block, Convulsions. Anorexia, gastric, ulcer, duodenal ulcer. GI haemorrhage, hepatitis, urinary incontinence, possibly bladder outflow obstruction.'),
(194, 'Povidone', 'Vaginal candidiasis. Treatment and prevention of wound infection. Oral hygiene. Oral candidiasis.', 'Hypersensitivity. Thyroid disorder. Lithium therapy. Pregnancy and lactation.', 'Renal impairment or electrolyte imbalance. Avoid contact with eyes.', 'Local sensitivity and reactions.'),
(195, 'Acetylcysteine', 'Tear deficiency. Acute cough associated with excessive or viscous mucus. Paracetamol poisoning.', 'Contraindicated during pregnancy and lactation.', 'Asthmatic patients, history of bronchospasm, peptic ulceration.', 'Flushing, fever, stomatitis, nausea, vomiting, rhinorrhoea, bronchospasm, anaphylactoid reactions, rashes. Rarely blurred vision, bradycardia, syncope, thrombocytopenia, convulsions. Rarely, resp or cardiac arrest.'),
(196, 'Methylergometrine', 'Active management of 3rd stage of labor. Postpartum and post abortion. Excessive uterine bleeding. Prevention and treatment of postpartum haemorrhage.', 'Pregnancy, 1st and 2nd stage of labour, patients with preeclampsia, eclampsia or threatened spontaneous abortion; porphyria.', 'Breech and abnormal foetal presentation; hypertension; chronic anaemia, hepatic, renal, resp or cardiac impairment, toxemia, lactation, hypocalcaemia. Monitor BP, pulse and uterine response.', 'Nausea, vomiting, rise in BP, decreased milk secretion, gangrene. Abdominal pain, diarrhoea, headache, dizziness, tinnitus, chest pain, palpitation, bradycardia, transient HTN and other cardiac arrhythmias, dyspnoea, sometimes rashes, shock MI, pulmonary oedema.'),
(197, 'Levo Norgestrel', 'Emergency contraception. Menopausal HRT.', 'Pregnancy, undiagnosed vag bleeding, severe arterial disease, liver, adenoma, porphyria, after recent evacuation of hydatidiform mole, history of breast cancer. Hepatic impairment.', 'Hypersensitivity. Sex steroid dependent cancer, past ectopic pregnancy, malabsorption syndromes, functional ovarian cysts, active liver disease, recurrent cholestatic jaundice, history of jaundice in pregnancy, CV or renal impairment. DM, asthma, epilepsy, migraine, conditions aggravated by fluid retention, depression and thromboembolism (high doses), lactation.', 'Nausea and vomiting, dizziness, fatigue, headache, abdominal pain, a feeling of breast tenderness. Menstrual irregularities, gynaecomastia, depression, skin disorders, disturbance of appetite, weight changes, fluid retention, oedema, changes in libido, cholestatic jaundice, hair loss or hirsutism. Benign intracranial hypertension, thrombocytopenic purpura. Thrombocytopenia, stroke.'),
(198, 'Capecitabine', 'It is used alone or in combination in the adjuvant and palliative treatment of gastrointestinal cancer and breast cancer.', 'History of severe and unexpected reaction to fluoropyrimidine therapy, severe renal impairment. Hypersensitivity. Contraindicated during pregnancy and lactation.', 'Hepatic dysfunction, bone marrow suppression, poor nutritional status, on warfarin therapy. Child, elderly, patients who received extensive pelvic radiation or alkylating therapy. Moderate renal impairment; CBC with differential hepatic and renal function should be monitored. Discontinue use if intractable diarrhoea, stomatitis, bone marrow suppression or myocardial ischaemia develops.', 'Diarrhoea, nausea and vomiting, stomatitis, palmar-plantar syndrome (erythema and desquamation of hands and feet), dermititis. fatique, mucosal inflammation, pyrexia, asthenia and lethargy; headache, dizziness and insomnia; lower limb oedema, anorexia, dehydration.'),
(199, 'Reserpine', 'Hypertension.', 'Hypersensitivity. Peptic ulcer disease. History of depressive illness especially in elderly. Epilepsy. Pregnancy. Parkinsons disease. Thyrotoxicosis. Pheochromocytoma.', 'Gastritis. Gall stones. Asthma or bronchitis. Cardiac failure. Myocardial infarction, Arrhythmias. Elderly or debilitated patients. Renal insufficiency. Lactation.', 'Depression. Suicidal tendency. Diarrhoea. APD miosis, sodium retention and weight gain. Nasal stuffiness. Breast engorgement, galactorrhoea, gynaecomastia, decreased libido. Impotence. Postural hypotension.'),
(200, 'Domperidone (IR)', 'Symptomatic relief of acute nausea and vomiting. Gastric motility disorders such as reflux oesophagitis and duodenogastric dyspeptic symptoms.', 'Hypersensitivity. GI haemorrhage, obstruction and perforation, patients with prolactin releasing pituitary hormone, chronic admin or routine prophylaxis of postoperative nausea and vomiting.', 'Phaeochromocytoma, children below two year, elderly, renal or hepatic impairment. Risk of cardiac arrhythmias and hypokalaemia if administered IV. Pregnancy and lactation.', 'Drowsiness, extrapyramidal reactions, galactorrhoea, gynaecomatia, constipation or diarrhoea, lassitude, decreased libido, skin rash, itch. Convulsions, arrhythmias and cardiac arrest, dysrrehythmias in patients with CV disease or hypokalaemia, patients on cancer chemotherapy. Seizure, hypertensive crisis in patients with phaeochromocytoma.'),
(201, 'Tropicamide', 'Mydriasis. Cycloplegia.', 'Narrow angle glaucoma. Hypersensitivity. Shallow anterior chamber.', 'Darkly pigmented lris is more resistant to pupillary dilatation and caution should be exercised to avoid overdosage. Elderly, children, pregnancy. Hypertension, hyperthyroidism, DM, Cardiac disorders.', 'Increased intra ocular pressure. Transient stinging, dry mouth, blurred vision, photophobia, tachycardia, headache, superficial punctate keratitis, systemic anticholinergic effects.'),
(202, 'Zonisamide', 'Refractory partial seizures.', 'Hypersensitivity. Lactation.', 'Pregnancy and children. Hepatic or renal impairment. History of nephrolithiasis.', 'Electrolyte impairment. GI disturbances. Headache, dizziness, ataxia, nystagmus, paraesthesia, confusion, difficulty concentrating, impaired memory, mental slowing, speech abnormalities, difficulty in verbal expression, agitation and/or irritability, depression, insomnia, schizohrenic behavior, somnolence, fatigue, ecchymosis, weight loss, rash, diplopia, decreased sweating, renal stones, pancreatitis, rhabdomyolysis. Stevens-Johnson syndrome, toxic epidermal necrolysis, blood dyscrasias.'),
(203, 'Etizolam', 'Anxiety, tension, depression, neurasthenic symptoms or sleep disorders in neurosis. Cervical vertebral disease, low back pain and tension headache.', 'Hypeersensitivity. Myasthenia gravis. Acute angle closure glaucoma. pregnancy and lactation. Serve respiratory failure or hepatic impairment.', 'Severe hepatic, renal, cardiac and cerebral organic disturbance. Children, elderly. May be impair ability to drive or operate heavy machinery.', 'Drowsiness, light-headedness, malaise, jaundice, thirst, nausea, retching, rash and weakness.'),
(204, 'Norgestrel', 'As contraceptive. Hormone replacement therapy (HRT). Dysfunctional uterine bleeding. Endrometriosis. Premenstrual syndrome/tension. Threatened/habitual abortion. Endometrial carcinoma. Dysmenorrhea. Suppression of postpartum lactation. Hypoventilation.', 'Hypersensitivity.Undiagnosed vaginal bleeding, breast cancer, pregnancy, lactation. Thromboembolic disorders. History of seizures. Markedly impaired liver functions.', 'Diabetes. Exclude pregnancy. Suspicion of thromboembolic disorders.', 'Breast engorgement, headache, rise in body temperature, edema, esophageal reflux, acne and mood swings may occur. Irregular bleeding or amenorrhoea. Long term use of progestin in HRT may increase the risk of breast cancer. Blood sugar may rise and diabetes may be precipitated by long-term use of potent agents like levonorgestrel. Given in early pregnancy, progestins can cause masculinization of female foetus and other congenital abnormalities.'),
(205, 'Olanzapine', 'Schizophrenia. Acute mixed or manic episodes in bipolar disorder.', 'Angle closure glaucoma. Hypersensitivity. History of CVS disease, heart surgery. Lactation.', 'Impaired renal, hepatic, CV function, prostatic hypertrophy paralytic ileus, DM, parkinsonism. Pregnancy. Hypotension, bradyarrhythmia, hypoventilation, monitor BP.', 'Orthostatic hypotension, interference with motor and cognitive performance, increase in transaminase levels. Occasionally dizziness and peripheral oedema. Increase in prolactin levels. Extrapyramidal symptoms may be less frequent than chlorpromazine. Neuroleptic malignant syndrome.'),
(206, 'Ibuprofen IP', 'Analgesic, antipyretic, dysmenorrhoea, rheumatoid arthritis, osteoarthritis, musculo skeletal disorders, soft tissue injuries, tooth extraction, post-partum and post operatively, acute gout. Juvenile idiopathic arthritis.', 'Active peptic ulcer, GI bleeding. Pregnancy and lactation. Hypersensitivity. Neonates with congenital heart disease.', 'Asthma, bleeding disorders, cardiovascular diseases and those receiving coumarin anticoagulants. Aspirin/anti-inflammatory induced allergy. Renal or hepatic disorders, CV disease.', 'GI intolerance, rash, rarely jaundice, thrombocytopenia oedema.'),
(207, 'Buprenorphine', 'Moderate to severe pain, cancer pain, pre-medication, postoperative pain and myocardial infarction.', 'Children below 16 kg.', 'Hepatic dysfunction, narcotic addicts. Labor, impaired respiratory functions. Avoid driving or operating machinery. Not recommended in children.', 'Sedation, vomiting, miosis. Postural hypotension, respiratory depression, dizziness, sweating.'),
(208, 'Alendronate Sodium', 'Treatment of postmenopausal osteoporosis. Pagets disease of bone. Corticosteroid-induced osteoporosis.', 'Hypocalcemia and hypersensitivity. Hypocalcaemia, causes of oesteoporosis.Patient with esophageal abnormalities. Contraindicated during pregnancy and lactation. Contraindicated to paediatrics.', 'Patient with acute upper gastrointestinal problem.', 'Abdominal pain, nausea, dyspepsia, constipation, diarrhoea, oesophageal ulcer, faltulence, acid regurgitation, vomiting, dysphalgia, abnormal distention, headache, musculoskeletal pain. Decrease in serum phosphate.'),
(209, 'Triamcinolone Acetonide', 'Atopic eczema. Allergic contact dermatitis. Lichen simplex. Primary irritant dermatitis. Seborrheic dermatitis. Psoriasis of face, flexures. Varicose eczema. Cystic acne. Alopecia areata. Discoid LE. Hypertrophied scars, keloids. Lichen planus. Nail disorders. Psoriasis of palm, sole, elbow, knee. A combination of steroid with proper antibiotic cover may also be used for: Impetigo, furunculosis, secondary infected dermatoses, napkin rash, otitis externa, intertriginous eruptions.', 'Hypersensitivity. Rosacea or perioral dermatitis. Primary infective skin. Pregnancy and lactation.', 'Infants. Secondary dermatological infections.', 'Thinning of epidermis. Dermal changes - atrophy. Telangiectasia, Striae. Easy bruising, Hypopigmentation. Delayed wound healing. Fungal and bacterial infections. Systemic adverse effects of topical steroids on prolong use: Adrenal pituitary suppression. Cushings syndrome.'),
(210, 'Dried Magnesium Sulphate', 'Replacement of hypomagnesemia. Tardes-de-pointis, cardiac arrest and quinide induced arrhythmia. Statis asthamaticus. Eclompsia (Pregnancy). Cerebral palsy in pre term basis. Barium Chloride poisoning. Topical Use -- Topical application over boils, carbundes and abseesses. Poultice form against blemishes. Soaking in warm bath can be beneficial to soothe, relax and relive herpes outbreak symptoms.', 'Hypersensitivity.', 'Drug allergy, kidney or heart disease, low blood calcium, myasthenia gravis, alcohol intake.', 'Flushing, sweating, muscle weakness, dizziness, drowsiness, breathing trouble.'),
(211, 'Loratadine', 'Allergic rhinitis, acute coryza, allergic dermatological disorders.', 'Hypersensitivity. Pregnancy and lactation. Children below the age of two years.', 'Severe hepatic damage, epilepsy, renal insufficiency.', 'Nausea, fatigue, headache giddiness, dizziness, somnolence.'),
(212, 'Abacavir', 'In combination with other antiretroviral agents for the treatment of HIV-1 infections.', 'It has been associated with fatal hypersensitivity reckoners hence should not be restarted after any hypersensitivity reaction occuring with abacavir.', 'Should always be used in combination with other antiretroviral agents.', 'Hypersensitivity reactions (fever, skin, rash, fatique, nausea, vomiting, diarrhoea or abdominal pain pharyngitis, dyspnoea or cough).'),
(213, 'Montelukast Sodium', 'Chronic asthma. Seasonal allergic rhinitis. Perennial allergic rhinitis. Prophylaxis of exercise-induced asthma.', 'Hypersensitivity. Pregnancy and lactation.', 'Not for the relief of acute bronchospasm. Not to be used as monotherapy for the prevention of exercise-induced bronchospasm. Patients in whom asthma is precipitated by aspirin or other NSAIDs should continue to avoid aspirin and NSAIDs.', 'Headache, rash, dyspepsia, dizziness, and abdominal pain, diarrhoea, sinusitis and otitis media. Aggression, agitation, angioedema, arthralgia, hypersensitivity, insomnia, muscle cramps, myalgia, nausea, pancreatitis.'),
(214, 'Timolol Maleate', 'Open angle glaucoma, aphakic glaucoma, secondary glaucoma. Raised intraocular pressure.', 'Hypersensitivity. Bronchial asthma, COPD, sinus bradycardia, 2nd and 3rd degree heart block, overt heart failure, cardiogenic shock. Pregnancy, lactation and children.', 'Due to systemic absorption. Heart block, cerebrovascular insufficiency, myasthenia gravis. May mask signs of hypoglycaemia, hyperthyroidism.', 'Transient burning sensation, blurred vision, mild ocular irritation. Bronchospasm. Reduction in resting heart rate and blood pressure. Fatigue, coldness of extremities, paraesthesia, GI symptoms, alopecia, decreased corneal sensitivity, visual disturbances, diplopia, ptosis, cystoid macular oedema.'),
(215, 'Lornoxicam', 'Rheumatoid arthritis. Osteoarthritis.', 'Peptic ulceration. Severe renal impairment. Pregnancy and lactation.', 'Active infections, asthma, allergic disorders, haemorrhagic disorders, hypertension, impaired renal, hepatic cardiac function.', 'Nausea, haematologic disorders, CNS effects. Abdominal pain, dizziness, diarrhoea, visual disturbance, tinnitus, nephrotoxicity, fluid retention, photosensitivity, alveolitis, toxic epidermal necrolysis, hypertension, insomnia, palpitation, somnolence, pancreatitis.'),
(216, 'Calcium Ascorbate', 'Calcium supplements are usually required where dietary calcium intake is deficient. This dietary requirement varies with age and is relatively greater in childhood, pregnancy and lactation due to an increased demand. Calcium supplement is also required in paused menopausal women and persons with osteopenia specially after the age of 60 years.', 'Patients with Calculi renal calculi or history of renal calculi; hypercalcaemia; hypophosphataemia.', 'Renal impairment, hypercalcaemia-associated disease eg. other malignancies; sarcoidosis; elderly.', 'Co-administration with thiazide diuretics or Vit D may lead to milk alkali syndrome and hypercalcaemia. Decreased absorption with coricosteroids. Decreases absorption of tetracyclinea, atenolol, iron, quinolones, alendronate, Na fluoride, Zn and calcium-channel blockers. Enhances cardiac effects of digitialis glycosides and may precipitate digitalis intoxication.'),
(217, 'Dipivefrine Hydrochloride', 'Chronic open angle glaucoma, other chronic glaucomas (as an adjuvant esp. to beta blockers).', 'Narrow angle glaucoma, hypersensitivity to dipivefrine.', 'Aphakic/Pseudophakic conditions. Hypersensitivity and/or intolerance to adrenaline, concurrent medication like indomethacin and ecothiophate. Lactation.', 'Ocular hyperaemia, burning, stinging sensation, follicular conjunctivitis, mydriasis, headache, eye pain, cardiovasular effects.'),
(218, 'Ormeloxifene', 'Dysfunctional uterine bleeding.', 'Jaundice or severe hepatic dysfunction. Polycystic ovarian disease. Chronic cervicitis or cervical hyperplasia. Hypersensitivity. Tuberculosis. Renal impairment. Pregnancy and lactation.', 'Bi-weekly or weekly dosage schedule had to be observed irrespective of menstrual periods. Ormeloxifene has contraceptive properties. Prolongation of menstrual cycle may be observed in some users.', 'Nausea, vomiting, headache and in some cases weight gain. Delayed menses.'),
(219, 'Urokinase', 'Acute myocardial infarction. Deep vein thrombosis. Pulmonary embolism. Peripheral vascular thrombo-embolism.', 'Hypersensitivity. Any purpuric or haemorrhagic disorder. Active gastro-intestinal or urinary tract bleeding. Severe hypertension. Pregnancy (1st 10 days post-partum). Sub acute bacterial endocarditis. Aneurysm. diathesis, peptic ulcer, oesophageal varices, ulcerative colitis or other bleeding GI lesions, pancreatitis, DM. Retinal vessel occlusion. Pregnancy.', 'Diabetic retinopathy. Arrhythmias when used in MI.', 'Fibrile reactions, haemorrhage. Anaphylic reactions.'),
(220, 'Bismuth Subcitrate', 'Gastritis and nonulcer dyspepsia associated with H.pylori.', 'Pregnancy and children.', 'Renal impairment.', 'Stools and tongue may become black. Diarrhoea, headache and dizziness. rolomnged use has the potential to cause osteodystrophy and encephalopathy.'),
(221, 'Chlorthalidone', 'Hypertension, oedema, toxaemia of pregnancy, prementrual tension. Diabetes Insipidus.', 'Severe renal impairment or anuria. Severe hepatic impairment, Addisons disease, preexisting hypercalcaemia, asthma, hypersensitivity, severe allergy. Contraindicated during pregnancy and lactation.', 'Existing fluid and electrolyte disturbances, hepatic cirrhosis, severe heart failure, hyperuricaemia, mild to moderate renal impairment. Elderly, monitor fluid and electrolyte balance. Kidney or liver disease, diabetes, gout, hyperlipidaemia and ventricular extra systoles', 'G.I. disturbance hearing loss acute saline depletion, allergic manifestations, carbohydrate intolerance, impotence, postural, hypotension, jaundice, cardiac arrhythmias, fatigue.'),
(222, 'Ethyl Morphine Hcl', 'Antitussive, strong analgesic. Less potent than morphine and more potent than codeine.', 'Infants and the elderly. Respiratory insufficiency. Bronchial asthma. Head injury. Hypotensive states. Undiagnosed acute abdominal pain.', 'Hypothyroidism, liver and kidney disease. Unstable personalities. Pregnancy and lactation.', 'Sedation, mental clouding, lethargy, vomiting, constipation, respiratory depression, blurring of vision, urinary retention, BP may fall.'),
(223, 'Lynestrenol', 'Polymenorrhoea, menorrhagia and metrorrhagia amenorrhoea and oligomenorrhoea. Premenstrual syndrome, endometriosis endometrial carcinoma. Benign breast disease. Supression of menstruation, ovulation and ovulation pain, dysmenorrhoea. Postponement of menstruation. Endometrial hyperplasia.', 'Pregnancy or suspected pregnancy. Severe liver disease. Rotor syndrome and Dubin-Johnson syndrome. Undiagnosed vaginal bleeding, herpes gestationis, jaundice of pregnancy, otosclerosis, severe pruritis or porphyria.', 'It may cause chloasma changes in parameters of liver function, carbohydrate metabolism and haemostasis, acne and hirsutism, circulatory disorders, depression.', 'Breakthrough bleeding or spotting, change in libido, nausea, GI disturbances, weight increase, headache, migraine, dizziness, nervousness, breast pain, oedema.'),
(224, 'Interferon Alpha 2A', 'Chronic hepatitis B and C infection. AIDS related Kaposis sarcoma. Condyloma acuminata caused by papilloma virus. H Simplex, H zoster and CMV infections in immuno compromised patients. Rhinoviral cold. Myelogenous leukaemia and multiple myeloma. Renal cell carcinoma. Hairy cell leukaemia. Follicular lymphoma. Cutaneous T-cell lymphoma. Melanoma.', 'Hypersensitivity. Auto immune hepatitis.', 'History of depression. Seizure disorders. Pre existing or any history of cardiac disease. Myelo suppression or concurrent use of myelo suppressive drugs. Hypothyroidism, hyperthyroidism, DM. Pregnancy and lactation.', 'Depression, suicidal behavior, irritability, insomnia, anxiety. Flu like symptoms. Headache, dizziness, paraesthesia, confusion, impaired concentration, alteration in taste or smell. GI disturbances. Dryness of oropharynx, epistaxis, rhinitis, sinusitis, arrhythmia. Alopecia, rash, dry skin or pruritus. Conjunctivitis, menstural irregularity, visual disturbances. Coughing, dsypnoea. Myalgia, joint or bone pain, arthritis or polyarthirits. Bone marrow depression. Marked increase in TG levels, GI haemorrhage, severe infections, pulmonary infiltrate or pulmonary function impairment.'),
(225, 'Hyoscine Butylbromide', 'Gastric and duodenal ulcers, gastro intestinal spasm and hypermotility, pylorospasm in infants, nausea and vomiting, spastic constipation, biliary dyskinesia and spasm of the urinary tract, delayed relaxation of the lower uterine segment, dysmenorrhoea. Motion sickness.', 'Glaucoma. Retention of urine (Prostate hypertrophy). Mechanical Stenosis in the region of GIT. Tachycardia. Megacolon. Acute haemorrhage, paralytic ileus, cardiac insufficiency, myasthenia gravis.', 'Hepatic/renal disease, pyloric stenosis, urinary retention, prostatic hyperplasia, psychosis, seizure disorders, ulcerative colitis, coronary artery disease, tachyarrhythmias, heart failure, hypertension. Elderly, children, pregnancy and lactation.', 'Increased pulse rate, vision disturbances due to IV administration. Tremor, weakness, impaired accommodation, blurred vision, cycloplegia.'),
(226, 'Pentoxifylline (Pentoxyphylline)', 'Non-haemorrhagic stroke. Chronic cerebrovascular insufficiency. Transient ischaemic attacks. Intermittent claudication due to arteriosclerotic, diabetic or inflammatory vascular disease. Trophic leg ulcer, gangrene.', 'Hypersensitivity. Acute M.I. Severe retinal or cerebral haemorrhage. Porphyria. Children.', 'Renal dysfunction. Severe coronary artery disease. Hypotension.', 'Nausea, vomiting, dyspepsia, bloating, flushing, vertigo.'),
(227, 'Escitalopram Oxalate', 'Treatment of major depressive disorder. Obsessive compulsive disorder. Panic disorder.', 'Concomitant use with MAOIs, hypersensitivity.', 'Mania, seizure disorders, works requiring mental alertness e.g. operating hazardous machinery, including automobiles, severe renal impairment, hepatic impairment.', 'Nausea, diarrhoea, increased sweating, insomnia,impotence, ejaculation disorder, fatique somnolence. Postural hypotension, sinusitis, taste disturbances. Increased appetite and weight gain.'),
(228, 'Methyldopa', 'Mild to moderate hypertension.', 'Phaeochromocytoma, depression, hepatic impairment. Hypersensitivity.', 'History of haemolytic anaemia, depression, parkinsonism, renal or hepatic impairment.', 'Sedation, lethargy, reduced mental capacity, dry mouth, fluid retention, weight gain, impotence, nasal congestion, postural hypotension. Sexual dysfunction, gynaecomastia, hyperprolactinaemia, thrombocytopenia, +ve Coombs test, transient leukopenia or granulocytopenia, cholestasis or hepatitis , haemolytic anaemia.'),
(229, 'Mirtazapine', 'Depression.', 'Hypersensitivity. Children.', 'Agranulocytosis. Interference with cognitive and motor performance. Patient should be cautioned about engaging in hazardous activities like driving, working on machines. Epilepsy, hepatic or renal impairment, cardiac disorders, DM, psychoses, angle-closure glaucoma, raised intraocular pressure. Pregnancy, lactation and elderly.', 'Increased appetite, asthenia, flu like syndrome, back pain. Dry mouth and constipation. Weight gain, peripheral oedema. Myalgia, dizziness, somnolence, abnormal dreams, abnormal thinking, tremor and confusion. Dyspnoea. Urinary frequency. Myalgia, reversible agranulocytosis, leucopenia, granulocytopenia, hyponatraemia.'),
(230, 'Aceclofenac', 'For the relief of pain and inflammation in osteoarthritis, rheumatoid arthritis and ankylosing spondylitis.', 'Hypersensitivity. GI bleeding. Moderate to severe renal impairment. Last three months of pregnancy.', 'Patients with GI disease, history of peptic ulceration, cerebrovascular bleeding, ulcerative colitis. Crohns disease, systemic lupus erythmatosus, porphyria, haematopoietic or coagulation disorders. The dose should be reduced in patients with mild to moderate hepatic, renal or cardiac function impairment.', 'Indigestion, heartburn, dyspepsia, diarrhoea, nausea, abdominal pain and flatulence.'),
(231, 'Topiramate', 'Partial seizures. Primary generalised tonic-clonic seizures. Seizure associated with Lennox Gastaut syndrome.', 'Lactation.', 'Pregnancy. Hepatic or renal impairment. Ensure proper hydration. May impair ability to drive or operate machinery.', 'Abdominal pain. Nausea and vomiting. Anorexia and weight loss. Impaired concentration. Emotional instability, mood disorders, depression, impaired speech, altered behaviour. Ataxia. Dizziness, drowsiness. Paresthesia. Fatique and asthenia. Migraine. Nystagmus. Visual disturbances. Cognitive problems. Leucopenia.'),
(232, 'Gonadotrophin', 'Amenorrhoea and infertility. Hypogonadotrophic hypogonadism in males. Cryptorchism. To aid in vitro fertilization.', 'Hypersensitivity. Hormone dependent malignancies (prostate, breast). Pituitary or ovarian tumour. Prostate carcinoma or androgen dependent neoplasms. Ovarian dys-genesis, absent uterus. Premature menopause. Tubal occulusion.', 'Ovarian hyperstimulation syndrome - Polycystic ovary. Precocious puberty. fluid retention is males.', 'Allergic reactions, headache, mental depression, ovarian hyperstimulation syndrome, gynaecomastia, Pain in lower abdomen and even ovarian bleeding and shock can occur in females.');
