(242, 'Phenazopyridine', 'Pain and irritability in cystitis, prostatitis and urethritis.', 'Pregnancy. Renal and hepatic impairment.', 'G6PD deficiency. Lactation.', 'Nausea, epigastric pains, abdominal discomfort. Headache, hepatotoxicity, haemolytic anaemia, methaemoglobinaemia, discoloration of urine and other body fluids.'),
(243, 'Tadalafil', 'Erectile dysfunction.', 'Men with cardiac disease for whom sexual activity is inadvisable. Recent MI (within 90 days) or stroke (within last 6 months), hypotension, unstable angina, heart failure, uncontrolled arrhythmias or hypertension.', 'Hepatic or renal impairment. Anatomical penile deformation.', 'Headache, dyspepsia, back pain, myalgia, nasal congestion, flushing and pain in limb. Swelling of eyelids, eye pain, hyperemia, back pain, myalgia, visual disturbances, nasal congestion, tinnitus. Sudden cardiac death.'),
(244, 'Pneumococcal Polyvalent Vaccine', 'Pneumococcal vaccination is recommended for individuals at increased risk of pneumococcal infection as follows: age over 65 years asplenia or splenic dysfunction (including homozygous sickle cell disease and coeliac disease which could lead to splenic dysfunction); chronic respiratory disease (includes asthma treated with continuous or frequent use of a systemic corticosteroid); chronic heart disease; chronic renal disease; chronic liver disease; diabetes mellitus requiring insulin or oral hypoglycaemic drugs; immune deficiency because of disease (e.g. HIV infection) or treatment (including prolonged systemic corticosteroid treatment); presence of cochlear implant; conditions where leakage of cerebrospinal fluid may occur; Child under 5 years with a history of invasive pneumococcal disease. Choice of vaccine- The 7-valent pneumococcal polysaccharide conjugate vaccine (PCV-7) is now a component of the primary course of childhood immunisation. The recommended schedule consists of 3 doses, the first at 2 months of age, the second at 4 months, and the third at 13 months. Children at increased risk should also receive a single dose of the 23-valent pneumococcal polysaccharide vaccine (PPV-23) after their second birthday. Children at increased risk of pneumococcal infection presenting late for vaccination should receive 2 doses (separated by at least 1 month) of pneumococcal polysaccharide conjugate vaccine (PCV-7) before the age of 12 months and a third dose at 13 months.', 'Hypersensitivity.', 'Do not freeze.', 'Anaphylactic reactions.'),
(245, 'Labetalol Hcl', 'All grades of hypertension. Specially useful in pheochromocytoma and clonidine withdrawal hypertension.', 'Children, allergic disorders with predisposition to bronchospasm, right ventricular failure, secondary to pulmonary hypertension. A.V. block greater than Ist degree, sinus bradycardia shock, CHF, pregnancy, lactation, anaesthesia with agents producing myocardial depression. Sick sinus syndrome, prinzmetrals angina, severe peripheral arterial disease.', 'Abrupt withdrawal, diabetes, cardiac failure, anaesthesia, hyperthyroidism,postural hypotension, eye and skin reaction, liver dysfunction.', 'Failure of ejaculation in males, headache, angina, jaundice, dreams, nightmares. Orthostatic hypotension, dizziness, fatigue, vertigo, paraesthesia, headache, nasal stuffiness, dysponea, diarrhoea, abdominal pain, sexual dysfunction, dyspepsia, nausea, vomiting, scalp tingling, rash, increased transaminases, nightmares, worsening of intermittent claudication. Hepatic injury.'),
(246, 'Glibenclamide IP', 'Non-insulin dependent diabetes mellitus.', 'Insulin-dependent diabetes mellitus, diabetic coma, severe metabolic decompensationn (Keto acidosis) severe renal impairment, severe infection or trauma. Hypersensitivity. Pregnancy, lactation and paediatrics.', 'Elderly, malnourished, mild to moderate renal and hepatic disorders. Impaired alertness. Avoid alcohol. Careful monitoring of blood-glucose concentration. Adrenocortical insufficiency. Avoid in severe hepatic impairment. Pregnancy and lactation.', 'Hypoglycaemia, cholestatic jaundice, agranulocytosis, aplastic anaemia, haemolytic anaemia. Blood dyscrasias (reversible), liver dysfunction, hypoglycaemia, GI symptoms, allergic skin reactions. Prolonged hypoglycaemia seen in elderly or debilitated patients with hepatic or renal diseases.'),
(247, 'Flutamide', 'Advanced prostatic cancer.', 'History of thromboembolic disorders. Severe chronic depression. Severe hepatic impairment. Pregnancy and lactation.', 'Monitor liver function tests periodically. Fluid retention can occur in patients with cardiac disease. Regular assessment of prostate specific antigen level may help to monitor disease progression. Exercise caution in patients with cardiac disease.', 'Nausea, vomiting, diarrhoea, stomatis, shedding of mucosa. Gynaecomastia, breast tenderness, glactorrhoea, insomnia, CNS disturbances. Hot flushes, loss of libido, impotence, increased appetite, sleep disturbances, skin reactions,, anaemias, headache, dizziness, malaise, anxiety, hypertension, gastric and chest pain, oedema, blurred vision, hepatitis, jaundice, rash, thirst, pruritus, SLE like syndrome, drowsiness, confusion, depression, nervousness.'),
