(476, 'Glucosamine Sulphate Potassium Chloride', 'Osteoarthritis and Rheumatoid arthritis.', 'Allergy to shellfish.', 'Diabetic patients, patients on heparin. Pregnancy and lactation.', 'Heart burn, epigastric pain/tenderness, diarrhoea, nausea, dyspepsia, constipation, abdominal pain, palpitations, drowsiness, skin reaction, headache, indigestion.'),
(477, 'Cefdinir', 'Community acquired pneumonia, otitis media, pharyngitis, tonsilitis, LRTI, Acute maxillary sinusitis, switch therapy, Acute exacerbation of chronic bronchitis, uncomplicated skin infections.', 'Contraindicated in patients with known allergy to cephalosporin class of antibiotics.', 'Caution to be take with patients hypersensitive to cephalosporins. It is not to be used during labour and delivery, paediatric use is not establlished.', 'Diarrhea, vaginal moniliasis, nausea, headache, abdominal pain, vaginitis, rash, flatulence, dyspepsia, vomiting, anorexia, constipation, dizziness, insomnia, pruritus, somnolence etc.'),
(478, 'Drotrecogin Alfa (Activated)', 'Anti- thrombotic, anti-inflammatory and profibronolytic properties. It is mainly used in intensive care unit as a conjunct treatment of severe sepsis. Although drotrecogin has potent anticoagulant properties, it is not indicated as an anticoagulant/anti thrombotic in patients without severe sepsis.', 'Hypersensitivity. Active internal bleeding. Within 3 months of haemorrhagic stroke. Within 2 months of intracranial/intraspinal surgery/severe head injury. Presence of epidural catheder. Known intracranial neoplasm.', 'Patients on anticoagulant therapy. Platelet count less than 30,000/mm3. Within 6 weeks of gastrointestinal bleeding. H/o bleeding diathesis. Within 3 months of ischaemic stroke. Known intracranial aneurysm or AV malfomation. HIV infection with CD count less than 50/mm3.', 'Ecchymosis, GI bleeding. Intracranial haemorrhage Life threatening bleeding. Hypersensitivity.'),
(479, 'Elemental Calcium', 'Calcium supplements are usually required where dietary calcium intake is deficient. This dietary requirement varies with age and is relatively greater in childhood, pregnancy and lactation due to an increased demand. Calcium supplement is also required in paused menopausal women and persons with osteopenia specially after the age of 60 years.', 'Patients with Calculi renal calculi or history of renal calculi; hypercalcaemia; hypophosphataemia.', 'Renal impairment, hypercalcaemia-associated disease eg. other malignancies; sarcoidosis; elderly.', 'Co-administration with thiazide diuretics or Vit D may lead to milk alkali syndrome and hypercalcaemia. Decreased absorption with coricosteroids. Decreases absorption of tetracyclinea, atenolol, iron, quinolones, alendronate, Na fluoride, Zn and calcium-channel blockers. Enhances cardiac effects of digitialis glycosides and may precipitate digitalis intoxication.'),
(480, 'Chlorpropamide', 'Type II diabetes myelitus.', 'Hepatic insufficiency (hepatitis, cirrhosis, steatosis). Renal impairment. Cardiovascular disease predisposing to tissue hypoxia. Alcohol intoxication. Surgery, stress and infections. Contraindicated during pregnancy and lactation. Contraindicated to paediatrics.', 'Alcohol even in moderation, Renal dysfunction. Congestive heart failure, Respiratory failure. Liver disease, Pancreatitis, Ischaemic vascular disease.', 'GI upset, leucopenia, thrombocytopenia, jaundice. Rashes, skin eruptions. Anaemia.'),
(481, 'Moclobemide', 'Depression.', 'Acute confusional states. Phaeochromocytoma.', 'Avoid in agitated or excited patients, thyrotoxicosis, severe hepatic impairment pregnancy and lactation.', 'Sleep disturbances, dizziness, nausea, headache, restlessness, agitation, confusional states. Possible hyponatremia. Hypertensive crisis.'),
(482, 'Trimethoprim', 'It is a bacteriostatic agent active against many gram positive and gram negative bacteria. It is maninly used in combination with sulfonamides because of similar activity. The combination is effective against additional organisms such as Salmonella typhi, Serratia, Klebsilla, Enterobacter, Yersenia enterocolitica, Pneumocystitis jiroveci and many sulfonamide resistant strains of Staph. aureus, Strep pyogenes, Shigella, Enteropathogenic E coli, H influenzae, Meningococci, and Gonococci.', 'Allergy, severe renal failure.', 'Early renal disease, geriatric patients, coadministration of diureties.', 'Nausea, vomiting, stomatitis, headache and rashes are the usual manifestations. Folate deficiency is infrequent, blood dyscrasias occur rarely.'),
(483, 'Hydroxyurea', 'Chronic myeloid leukaemia. Solid tumours. Psoriasia, polychthaemia.', 'Marked bone marrow depression, severe anaemia. Pregnancy and lactation.', 'Periodic hematological monitoring, renal and hepatic function monitoring, recent radiotherapy or cytotoxic therapy, elderly and children.', 'Bone marrow suppression, including megaloblastic changes. Erythema caused by irradiation may be exacerbated by hydroxyurea. Gastrointestinal disturbances, impairment of renal function, pulmonary oedema, mild dermatological reaction, pulmonary oedema, mild dermatological reactions, alopecia and neurological reactions.'),
(484, 'Zidovudine', 'Asymptomatic and symptomatic HIV disease. Prophylaxis of maternal-foetal HIV transmission. Prophylaxis of HIV infection in neonates.', 'Hypersensitivity. Lactation. Neutropenia.', 'Hepatic or renal impairment. Elderly, pregnancy. Anaemia. Myelo suppression.', 'Anorexia, myalgia, insomnia, nausea, rash, abdominal pain, fever, anaemia, neutropenia, leucopenia. Dizziness, taste perversion, convulsions, myopathy, nail, skin and oral mucosa pigmentation, pancreatitis, fat redistribution. Lactic acidosis, severe hepatomegaly. Blood dyscrasias.'),
(485, 'Duloxetine', 'Major depressive disorders.Moderate to severe stress urinary incontinence in women. Diabetic neuropathy.', 'Hypersensitivity. Narrow angle glaucoma, severe hepatic disease, suicidal ideation, bipolar disorders, epilepsy, hypertension. Lactation.', 'Avoid alcohol and abrupt cessation. May impair ability to drive or engage in task requiring alertness. Increased risk of suicidal thinking and behavior when used in child and adolescents. Pregnancy.', 'Anorexia, constipation, diarrhoea, nausea, vomiting, gastritis, dizziness, drowsiness, insomnia, anxiety, fatigue, cramps, tremors, hyperhydrosis, xerostomia, weight loss, dysurea, flushing, blurred vision, acne vulgaris, pruritus of skin, skin rash, alopecia, dry mouth, decreased appetite, somnolence, increased sweating, disorder of ejaculation, orgasm disorder.'),
(486, 'Ethambutol HcI IP', 'Primary treatment of pulmonary and extrapulmonary.', 'Hypersensitivity, Optic neuritis. Lactation.', 'Impaired pre-treatment visual acuity, elderly, children. Perform liver, kidney and visual acuity tests regularly. Caution when assessing visual acuity in patients with cataracts. DM, recurrent eye inflammation to make sure that changes are not due to the underlying.', 'Retrobulbar neuritis with a reduction in visual acuity, constriction of visual field, central or peripheral scotoma and green-red color blindness. Retinal haemorrhage (rare), reduced renal clearance of urates (acute gout), GI disturbances e.g nausea, vomiting, abdominal pain, anorexia, rash, headache, dizziness, confusion, hallucinations, malaise, jaundice, thrombocytopenia, pulmonary infiltrates.'),
(487, 'H.Influenzae B Vaccine', 'Immunization of children between 2 months to 6 years against Haemophilus influenzae type B, which is responsible for meningitis, septicaemia, cellulitis, arthritis, epiglotitis and chest infection in children. Splenectomy or Asplenemia.', 'Hypersensitivity.', 'Congulation disorders, acute febrile illnessess and immunosuppressed patients.', 'Allergic reactions.'),
