(495, 'Flunarizine', 'Migraine prophylaxis, prophylaxis of peripheral and cerebrovascular disorders. Prophylaxis of vertigo and vestibular disorders.', 'GI or urinary tract obstruction, acute porphyrias. Pregnancy and lactation.', 'Epilepsy, elderly, CVS disease, glaucoma.', 'Drowsiness, weight gain, headache, depression, gastric pain, dry mouth, insomnia and extrapyramidal reactions.'),
(496, 'Benzthiazide (Benzothiazide)', 'Mild to moderate cases of oedema, preferred for manintenace therapy. It is sually used in combination with potassium sparing diuretres and is best in cardiac oedema, less effective in renal or hepatic oedema.', 'Severe renal and heaptic impairment, refrectory edema, hyperkalaemia allergy ro thiazides.', 'To be used in combination with potassium sparing diuretics.', 'Nausea, vomiting, fatique, urinary problems, drowsiness, electrolyte imbalance and allergic reactions.'),
(497, 'Theophylline', 'Reversible airway obstructive diseases.', 'Hypersensitivity.', 'Cardiac failure, hypertension, epilepsy, hyperthyroidism, history of peptic ulcer disease, renal or hepatic dysfunction, glaucoma, DM, severe hypoxaemia, chronic alcoholism, acute febrile illness. Pregnancy, lactation, children and elderly.', 'Nausea, vomiting, abdominal pain, diarrhoea, headache, insomnia, dizziness, anxiety, restlessness, tremor, palpitations. Convulsions, cardiac arrhythmias, hypotension and sudden death after too rapid IV inj.'),
(498, 'Amlodipine Besilate', 'Mild to moderate hypertension. Angina pectoris. Prinzmetals angina.', 'Hypersensitivity.', 'Impaired liver or renal function, CHF, sick sinus syndrome, severe ventricular dysfunction, hypertrophic cardiomyopathy, severe aortic stenosis. Idiopathic hypertrophic subaortic stenosis. Elderly, children, pregnancy and lactation.', 'Peripheral edema, headache, dizziness, flushing and abdominal pain. Fatigue, somnolence, nausea, dyspepsia, palpitations, pruritus, rash, muscle cramps.'),
(499, 'Human Albumin', 'Hypoproteinaemia. Hypovolaemic shock. Burns. Used in exchange transfusion in neonatal jaundice.', 'Hypersensitivity. Volume overload. Circulatory failure.', 'Accelerated phase of hypertension. Fluid overload. Very low cardiac output.', 'Allergic reactions.'),
(500, 'Hydrocortisone Sodium Succinate', 'Replacement therapy: Adrenal insufficiency. Adrenogenital syndrome. Nonendocrine diseases: Rheumatoid arthirits. Osteoarthritis, Acute gouty arthirits. Collagen diseases e.g. systemic lupus erythematosus, polyarteritis nodosa, dermatomyositis, nephritic syndrome, glomerulonephritis and related diseases. Severe allergic reactions e.g. anaphylaxis, angioneurotic edema, urticaria and serum sickness and related diseases. Autoimmune diseases e.g. haemolytic anaemia, idiopathic thrombocytopenic purpura, active chronic hepatitis and related diseases. Other lung diseases e.g. pulmonary edema, accelerate lung maturation and surfactant production in the foetus and prevent respiratory distress syndrome at birth. Infective diseases e.g. severe forms of tuberculosis, severe lepra reaction, certain forms of bacterial meningitis and Pneumocystis carinii pneumonia with hypoxia in AIDS patients along with proper antibiotic cover. Eye diseases e.g. inflammatory ocular diseases, allergic conjunctivitis, iritis, iridocyclitis, keratitis, retinitis, optic neuritis, uveitis. Skin diseases e.g. eczematous skin diseases. Pemphigus vulgaris, exfoliative dermatitis, Stevens Johnson syndrome. Intestinal diseases e.g. ulcerative colitis, Crohns disease, coeliac disease are chronic inflammatory intestinal diseases. Cerebral edema. Malignancies e.g. Acute lymphatic leukaemia, Hodgkins and other lymphomas. Hormone responsive breast carcinoma. Organ transplantation and skin allograft. Septic shock. Thyroid storm.', 'Viral, fungal, tuberculous or purulent infections unless until treated with proper antibiotic concurrently. Pregnancy. New born babies, premature infants or children below the age of five years. Peptic ulcer. Psychosis. Epilepsy. Renal failure. Osteoporosis. In ophthalmology, herps zoster, herpetic or fungal xeratitis, previous history of cataract.', 'Prolong use. CHF, hypertension, DM. Elderly and lactation.', 'Cushings habitus. Peptic ulceration may be aggravated. Sodium and fluid retention. Potassium and Calcium depletion. Muscle wasting, osteoporosis. GI disturbances and bleeding. Increased appetite and delayed wound healing. Bruising, striae, hirsutism, acne, flushing. Headache, depression, psychosis, menstrual irregularity. Suppression of pitutary-adrenocortical system. Dermal atrophy. Hyperglycaemia. Susceptibility to infection. Osteoporosis. Growth retardation. Foetal abnormalities. Topical application to the eye can produce corneal ulcers, raised IOP, reduced visual function and posterior subcapsular cataract.'),
(501, 'Human Anti-D Immoune globulin', 'Prevention of development of Anti-D antibodies in Rh negative mothers after child birth. For immunosuppression in organ transplantation. Autoimmune purpura.', 'Hypersensitivity to blood products. Rh-o(D) positive or D-u positive. Rh-o(D) negative or D-u negative patient.', 'Concomitant administration of live vaccines.', 'Increased risk of bacterial, fungal, viral (especially CMV) as well as opportunistic infections. Development of lymphomas and related malignancies after a long latency.'),
(502, 'Methyl Ergometrine Maleate', 'Active management of 3rd stage of labor. Postpartum and post abortion. Excessive uterine bleeding. Prevention and treatment of postpartum haemorrhage.', 'Pregnancy, 1st and 2nd stage of labour, patients with preeclampsia, eclampsia or threatened spontaneous abortion; porphyria.', 'Breech and abnormal foetal presentation; hypertension; chronic anaemia, hepatic, renal, resp or cardiac impairment, toxemia, lactation, hypocalcaemia. Monitor BP, pulse and uterine response.', 'Nausea, vomiting, rise in BP, decreased milk secretion, gangrene. Abdominal pain, diarrhoea, headache, dizziness, tinnitus, chest pain, palpitation, bradycardia, transient HTN and other cardiac arrhythmias, dyspnoea, sometimes rashes, shock MI, pulmonary oedema.'),
(503, 'Pefloxacin', 'Urinary tract infections. Gonorrhoea. Chancroid. Bacterial gastroenteritis. Typhoid. Bone. Respiratory infections. Gram-negative septicaemias. Meningitis. Conjunctivitis.', 'Hypersensitivity. Pregnancy, lactation and. children below the age of fifteen years. Epilepsy.', 'Avoid exposure to ultraviolet light. Hepatic insufficiency. Concomitant use of aluminium and magnesium containing antacids.', 'Gastro intestinal disturbances, muscle and joint pains. Photosensitivity reactions, neurological disturbances (headache, insomnia), thrombocytopenia (at doses of 1600 mg daily) may occur. Pseudomembranous colitis and superinfections. Epigastric stress, nauses and vomiting, apigastic pain, skin rashes, arthralgia. May precipitate convulsions.'),
(504, 'Erythromycin Estolate IP', 'Upper respiratory tract infections. Acute pneumonia. Vaginitis due to Chlamydia trachomatis. Impetigo. Wound and burn infections. Infected eczema. Acne vulgaris. Sycosis vulgaris.', 'Hypersensitivity. Pregnancy and lactation.', 'Interacts with theophyline, digoxin, carbamazepine and oral anticoagulants. Keep away from the eyes, nose, mouth and other mucous membranes.', 'Mild to severe epigastric pain. Diarrhoea. Allergic reactions. Skin - dryness, erythema, pruritus, desquamation and rarely burning. Hepatitis with cholestatic jaundice resembling viral hepatitis or extra hepatic billary obstruction and reversible abnormalities in LFTs may be associated with prolonged or repeated therapy.'),
(505, 'Dapsone', 'Drug of choice for all forms of leprosy.', 'Hypersensitivity.', 'Treatment should be initiated with a small dose and to be increased gradually.', 'Hemolysis of varying degree, Methemoglobinemia and Heinz-body formation, anorexia, nausea, vomiting, headache, nervousness, insomnia, blurred vision, erythema nodosumleprosum.'),
(506, 'Gefitinib', 'Locally advanced or metastatic non-small cell lung cancer after failure of both platinum based and docetaxel chemotherapies.', 'Hypersensitivity. Pregnancy, lactation and paediatrics.', 'Hepatic or severe renal impairment.', 'Diarrhoea, rash, acne, dry skin, nausea and vomiting.'),
(507, 'Amphotericin B', 'Topically for oral, vaginal and cutaneous candidiasis and otomycosis. Most effective for various types of systemic mycoses.', 'Renal impairment, epilepsy.', 'Test dose is must before giving intravenously. Adverse reactions can decrease with inclusion of hydrocortisone 0.6 mg/kg body weight in the infusion.', 'Chills, fever, aches, nausea, vomiting and dyspnoea. Thromboflebitis of the injected vein. Nephrotoxicity, (azotemia, reduced g.f.r. acidosis, hypokalemia and inability to concentrate urine). Anaemia due to bone marrow depression. CNS toxicity.'),
(508, 'Calcium D-Pantothenate', 'Biliary colic, dysmenorrhoea, intestinal colic, renal colic.', 'Narrow angle glaucoma, prostatic hypertropy, mechanical obstruction.', 'Thyrotoxicosis, obstructive airway disease, pyrexia, elderly and during cardiac surgery.', 'Allergy, atropine like side effects.'),
(509, 'Ethionamide', 'Second line anti-tubercular drug. Leprosy.', 'Hypersensitivity, severe liver disease, porphyria.', 'Difficulty in managing DM. Monitor blood glucose, thyroid and visual function. Perform LFT before and during treatment. Caution in patients with psychiatric illness or depression. Pregnancy and lactation.', 'Anorexia, nausea and vomiting, metalic taste, abdominal pain, diarrhoea, severe postural hypotension, mental depression and drowsiness, blurred vision, olfactory disturbances (alterations in smell), dizziness, headache, restlessness and tremors. Peripheral and/or optic neuritis, psychiatric disturbances, e.g. depression, anxiety, psychosis, postural hypotension. Jaundice, hepatitis. Thrombocytopenia, skin rashes, stomatitis.'),
