(608, 'Nefopam', 'Acute and chronic pain including post operative, dental, cancer, musculo-skeletal and traumatic.', 'Children, convulsions and CNS disorders. Myocardial infarction.', 'Renal and hepatic dysfunction, urinary retention.', 'Dry mouth, dizziness, nausea, nervousness, blurred vision, sweating, insomnia, headache, tachycardia, urinary retention.'),
(609, 'Prochlorperazine Mesylate', 'Psychoses. Nausea and vomiting. Severe anxiety disorders. Vertigo.', 'CNS depression, comatose patients. Bone marrow depression, phaechromocytoma, prolactin-dependent tumours. Hypersensitivity. Pregnancy, lactation and children below the age of two years.', 'Extrapyramidal syndrome, epilepsy, impaired hepatic, renal, CV, cerebrovascular or respiratory function. History of jaundice, myasthenia gravis, paralytic ileus and prostatic hyperplasia.', 'Cholestatic jaundice, cardiac arrhythmias, orthostatic hypotension, leucopaenia, thrombocytopaenia, dry mouth, blurring of vision, glaucoma, urinary retention, constipation, galactorrhoea, gynaecomastia, numbness of gum and tongue. Bone marrow suppression.'),
(610, 'Insulin (Bovine) Protamine Zinc', 'Conventional insulin produced from beef or pork pancreas. Since 1970 improved purified insulins are available. i) Purified by gel filtration. ii) Purified by Ion exchange chromatography. iii) Highly purified or mono component (MC). Type I DM. Type II DM not controlled by oral drugs. Diabetic ketoacidosis (Diabetic coma). Hyperosmolar (nonketotic hyperglycaemic coma). During septecemia or surgical procedures.', 'Hypersensitivity. Hypoglycaemia and insulinoma.', 'Renal impairment. Ischemic heart disease. Combination therapy. Insulin resistance.', 'Hypoglycaemia, development of antibodies to insulin, hypersensitivity, local Lipodystrophy, Oedema. Local reaction at injection site.'),
(611, 'Aspirin', 'Prophylaxis in cases of increased risk of blood clotting. Myocardial infarction, coronary bypass, transluminal angioplasty, strokes, transient ischaemic attack. Analgesic (Headache, backache, myalgia, joint pain, toothache, neuralgias, dysmenorrhoea). Antipyretic.', 'Hypersensitivity, haemophilia, hypoprothrombinaemia, platelet disorders, active peptic ulceration and other bleeding disorders. Children suffering from chicken pox or influenza. Avoided in diabetics and injuvenile rheumatoid arthritis and should be stopped before surgery. Contraindicated during pregnancy. Contraindicated below the age of twelve years.', 'May precipitate bronchospasm and induce asthmatic attacks in susceptible subjects. Gastrointestinal haemorrhage. Gout.', 'G.I. discomfort, nausea, vomiting. Epigastric distress, occult blood loss in stools, dizziness, tinnitus, vertigo, impairment of hearing and vision, excitement and mental confusion, hyperventilation and electrolyte imbalance. Drug interaction following concurrent use of aspirin with heparin, coumarin or corticoid derivatives, methotrexate, sulfonylureas, probenecid and sulfinpyrazone and spironolactone. It potentiates antiplatelet action of dipridamole.'),
(612, 'Hydroxycarbamide (Hydroxyurea)', 'Chronic myeloid leukaemia. Solid tumours. Psoriasia, polychthaemia.', 'Marked bone marrow depression, severe anaemia. Pregnancy and lactation.', 'Periodic hematological monitoring, renal and hepatic function monitoring, recent radiotherapy or cytotoxic therapy, elderly and children.', 'Bone marrow suppression, including megaloblastic changes. Erythema caused by irradiation may be exacerbated by hydroxyurea. Gastrointestinal disturbances, impairment of renal function, pulmonary oedema, mild dermatological reaction, pulmonary oedema, mild dermatological reactions, alopecia and neurological reactions.'),
(613, 'Codeine Phosphate', 'Mild to moderate pain; diarrhoea ; cough suppression', 'Acute respiratory depression, paralytic ileus, conditions associated with raised intracranial pressure and head injury and convulsive disorders. Alcoholisms. Pregnancy.', 'Hypothyroidism, adrenocortical insufficiency, asthma, impaired hepatic or renal function, prostatic hyperplasia, hypotension, shock, inflammatory or obstructive bowel disorders, myasthenia gravis. Infants, neonates. Rdduce dose in elderly or debilitated patients. May impair ability drive or operate machinery. Lactation.', 'Constipation.'),
(614, 'Ferrous Fumarate IP', 'Iron deficiency either due to chronic blood loss or poor absorption.', 'Iron intolerance.', 'History peptic ulcer, severe renal failure. Iron and tetracycline bind together leading to impairment of absorption.', 'GI upset, black stools, abdominal discomfort or pain by oral therapy.'),
(615, 'Isoxsuprine Hcl', 'Premature labor, threatened or habitual abortion. Cerebral and peripheral vascular disease.', 'Presence of recent aterial haemorrhage. Acute coronary thrombosis.', 'Severe angina pectoris. Hyperthyroidism, recent myocardial lesion, paroxysmal tachycardia. Pregnancy and lactation.', 'Dizziness, nausea, vomiting, hypertension, palpitation, rash, abdominal disturbances, hypotension. Maternal pulomary oedema and foetal tachycardia (IV).'),
(616, 'Pseudoephedrine', 'Nasal decongestant.', 'Hypertension, phaeochromocytoma.', 'Diabetes. Hyperthyroidism, ischaemic heart disease, arrhythmias or tachycardia, occlusive vascular disorders, aneurysms, closed-angle glaucoma, renal impairment, prostatic enlargment. Pregnancy and lactation.', 'Anginal pain, anxiety, restlessness, tremor, insomnia, confusion, irritability, reduced appetite, nausea, vomiting.'),
(617, 'Sodium Nitroprusside', 'Hypertensive crisis. Controlled hypotension. Refractory CHF. Pump failure accompanying MI. Acute mitral regurgitation.', 'Hypothyroidism.', '', 'Palpitation, nervousness, vomiting, perspiration, pain in abdomen, weakness, disorientation, psychosis and lactic acidosis.'),
(618, 'Estrogens', 'Menopause (Hormone replacement therapy). Oral contraception. Threatened or habitual abortion. Dysmenorrhea. Dysfunctional uterine bleeding. Failure of ovarian development Hirsuitism. Senile osteoporosis. Post menopausal osteoporosis. Breast cancer. Prostatic carcinoma. Suppression of post partum lactation. Senile vaginitis. Delayed puberty in girls. Acne (Not usually given).', 'Pregnancy. Thromboembolic disorders, coronary and cerebrovascular diseases or a history of it.. Moderate-to-severe hypoertension, hyperlipidaemia. Active liver disease, hepatoma or history of jaundice during past pregnancy. Suspected.overt malignancy of genitals/breast. Prophyria. Impending major surgery - avoid post-operative thromboembolism.', 'Diabetes: control may be vitiated. Obesity. Smoking. Undiagnosed vaginal bleeding. Uterine leiomyoma: may enlarge with estrogenic preparations, progestin only pills can be used. Mentally ill. Age above 35 years. Mild hypertension. Migraine. Gallbladder disease.', 'Thromboembolic disorders. Coronary and cerebral thrombosis. Rising BP. Lipid disorders. Genital carcinoma. Benign hepatoma. Gall stones. Weight gain. Chloasma. Pruritus Vulvae. DM. Emotional instability. Nausea, Vomiting, headache, breath through bleeding, breast discomfort. Suppression of libido, gynaecomastia and feminization when given to males. Fusion of epiphyses and reduction of adult stature when given to children. Stilbestrol given to pregnancy women, especially during first trimester increases the incidence of vaginal and cervical carcinoma in female off spring. In postmenopausal women, estrogens can increase the risk of irregular bleeding and endometrial carcinoma. Estrogens can accelerate the growth of existing breast cancer. Migraine, epilepsy and endometriosis may be worsened by estrogens.'),
(619, 'Lithium Carbonate', 'Acute hypomania, mania, recurrent mania. Depression. Prophylaxis of MDP. Recurrent neuropsychiatric illness. ADH secretion syndrome.', 'Pregnancy,lactation and children. CNS disorders. Severe renal and cardiac disease, severe dehydration, Sodium depletion, debilitation.', 'Monitor renal and thyroid functions. Maintain salt and fluid intake. Drug interaction occurs with phenytoin, carbamazepine, haloperidol, diazepam, methyldopa, tetracycline, diuretics.', 'Nausea, vomiting, mild diarrhoea initially. Thirst and polyuria. Fine tremors and rarely seizures. CNS toxicity-coarse tremors, giddiness, ataxia, motor in coordination, nystagmus, mental confusion, slurred speech, hyper reflexia. Exacerbation of psoriasis, acne, hypothyroidism.'),
(620, 'Sulfadoxine', 'Chloroquine resistant falciparum malaria. Pneumocystis pneumonia in AIDS. Toxoplasmosis.', 'Hypersensitivity. Infants', 'Pregnancy.', 'Severe anaphylaxis reactions.'),
(621, 'Citalopram', 'Treatment of depressive illness in the initial phase and as maintenance against potential relapse/recurrence. Treatment of panic disorder with or without agarophobia.', 'Hypersensitivity. Contraindicated during pregnancy and lactation.', 'Should not be given to patients receiving monoamine oxidase inhibitors, or for 14 days after their discontinuation.', 'Increased sweating, headache, tremor, dizziness, sleep disorder, agitation, nervousness, nausea, GI distutbances, palpitation, asthenia, rash, pruritus, migraine, abnormal vision, decreased libido, impaired concentration, amnesia, anxiety, suicidal tendency.'),
(622, 'Salbutamol', 'Reversible airways obstruction. Premature labour.', 'Cardiovascular disease. Eclampsia and severe pre-eclampsia, intra-uterine infection, intra-uterine foetal death, antepartum haemorrhage, placenta praevia and cord compression, threatened miscarriage, cardiac disease.', 'Hypertensive ischaemic heart disease. Receiving digitalis.', 'Arrythmias. Tremors, Palpitation, restlessness, nervousness, throat irritation and ankle edema. Tremor, muscle cramps, headache, hypokalaemia.'),
(623, 'Calcium Orotate', 'Calcium supplements are usually required where dietary calcium intake is deficient. This dietary requirement varies with age and is relatively greater in childhood, pregnancy and lactation due to an increased demand. Calcium supplement is also required in paused menopausal women and persons with osteopenia specially after the age of 60 years.', 'Patients with Calculi renal calculi or history of renal calculi; hypercalcaemia; hypophosphataemia.', 'Renal impairment, hypercalcaemia-associated disease eg. other malignancies; sarcoidosis; elderly.', 'Co-administration with thiazide diuretics or Vit D may lead to milk alkali syndrome and hypercalcaemia. Decreased absorption with coricosteroids. Decreases absorption of tetracyclinea, atenolol, iron, quinolones, alendronate, Na fluoride, Zn and calcium-channel blockers. Enhances cardiac effects of digitialis glycosides and may precipitate digitalis intoxication.'),
(624, 'Benazepril', 'Hypertension. Congestive heart failure.', 'Hypersensitivity. Angioedema. Bilateral renal artery stenosis. Pregnancy.', 'Renal impairment. Renal artery stenosis. Hyperkalaemia. Valvular stenosis. Immunosuppressive therapy. Lactation.', 'Headache, dizziness, fatigue, cough, somnolence, nausea and postural dizziness. Transient elevations in BUN and serum creatinine. palpitations, constipation, gastritis, melena, rash, pruritus, musculoskeletal pain, paraesthesia, anxiety, hyperkalaemia, leucopenia and flushing. Angioedema (rare).'),
(625, 'Alfa-beta Arteether', 'Severe falciparum malaria, cerebral malaria, multidrug resistant malaria.', 'Contraindicated during pregnancy.', 'Avoid concomitant use of drugs known to prolong QT interval, renal/hepatic disease. Avoid combination with pyrimethamine/sulphadoxine.', 'Decrease in reticulocyte count, slight rise of ALAT and ASAT may occur.'),
(626, 'Calciferol', 'Managing hypocalcemia in patients undergoing dialysia for chronic renal failure. Renal osteodystrophy. Hypocalaemia and Hyperphosphataemia. Vitamin D dependent rickets, renal tubular osteomalacia.', 'Hypercalcemia, evidence of Vitamin D toxicity, malabsorption syndrome, hypervitaminosis D, abnormal sensitivity to the effects of Vitamin D, decreased renal function. Contraindicated during pregnancy and lactation.', 'Pediatric doses must be individualized and monitored under close medical supervision, Idiopathic hypercalcemia, renal function impairment. Coronary disease renal function impairment and arteriosclerois, especially in the elderly. Hypoparathyroidism.', 'Dry mouth, muscle pain, polydipsia, anorexia, reversible azotemia, vomiting, pancreatitis, mild acidosis, metallic taste, rhinorrhea.');
