(682, 'Tolbutamide', 'Type II diabetes mellitus.', 'Hypersensitivity. Type I diabetes meliitus. Diabetic ketoacidosis. Severe renal impairment. Pregnancy, lactation and children.', 'Alcoholism. Hepatic adrenocortical or thyroid function impairment. Stress due to surgery or trauma, history of hepatic porphyria.', 'Hypoglycaemia, nausea, epigastric fullness, heartburn, headache, allergic skin reactions, jaundice, hyponatraemia, hepatic dysfunction, photosensitivity, syndrome of inappropriate secretion of antidiuretic hormone (SIADH) and blood dyscrasias.'),
(683, 'Granisetron Hcl', 'Nausea and vomiting induced by cytotoxic chemotherapy and radiotherapy. Prophylaxis and treatment of postoperative nausea and vomiting.', 'Hypersensitivity. Contraindicated below the age of two years.', 'Subacute intestinal obstruction or ileus. Moderate to severe hepatic impairment. Congenital long QT syndrome or other risk factors for QT prolongation. Pregnancy and lactation.', 'Anxiety, fever, headache, asthenia, somnolence, dizziness, insomnia. Elevation of liver enzymes (AST & ALT). Constipation, hypersensitivity reactions, chest pain, CV disturbances, visual disturbances, development of seizures, extrapyramidal reactions.'),
(684, 'Hydrocortisone -17 Butyrate', 'Atopic eczema. Allergic contact dermatitis. Lichen simplex. Primary irritant dermatitis. Seborrheic dermatitis. Psoriasis of face, flexures. Varicose eczema. Cystic acne. Alopecia areata. Discoid LE. Hypertrophied scars, keloids. Lichen planus. Nail disorders. Psoriasis of palm, sole, elbow, knee. A combination of steroid with proper antibiotic cover may also be used for: Impetigo, furunculosis, secondary infected dermatoses, napkin rash, otitis externa, intertriginous eruptions.', 'Hypersensitivity. Rosacea or perioral dermatitis. Primary infective skin. Pregnancy and lactation.', 'Infants. Secondary dermatological infections.', 'Thinning of epidermis. Dermal changes - atrophy. Telangiectasia, Striae. Easy bruising, Hypopigmentation. Delayed wound healing. Fungal and bacterial infections. Systemic adverse effects of topical steroids on prolong use: Adrenal pituitary suppression. Cushings syndrome.'),
(685, 'Calcium gluconolactobionate', 'Calcium supplements are usually required where dietary calcium intake is deficient. This dietary requirement varies with age and is relatively greater in childhood, pregnancy and lactation due to an increased demand. Calcium supplement is also required in paused menopausal women and persons with osteopenia specially after the age of 60 years.', 'Patients with Calculi renal calculi or history of renal calculi; hypercalcaemia; hypophosphataemia.', 'Renal impairment, hypercalcaemia-associated disease eg. other malignancies; sarcoidosis; elderly.', 'Co-administration with thiazide diuretics or Vit D may lead to milk alkali syndrome and hypercalcaemia. Decreased absorption with coricosteroids. Decreases absorption of tetracyclinea, atenolol, iron, quinolones, alendronate, Na fluoride, Zn and calcium-channel blockers. Enhances cardiac effects of digitialis glycosides and may precipitate digitalis intoxication.'),
(686, 'Lumefantrine (Banflumetol)', 'Antimalarial drug and only used in combination with artemether to treat Falciparum malaria.', 'Prophylaxis, hypersensitivity, history of prolonged QT interval in the family.', 'Birth control pills.', 'Headache, dizziness, weakness, muscle or joint pain, vomiting, loss of appetite, cardiac arrhythmia, fainting, hypersensitivity.'),
(687, 'Human Normal Immunoglobulin', 'A gammaglobulinemia, severe infections in immunodeficient patients or neonates. Now rarely used as prophylaxis, in Hepatitis A or Hepatitis B infections. Prevent or modify measles attack in Immunocomppromised patients. Primary rubella in pregnant women whereby pregnancy termination is unacceptable. Idiopathic thrombocytopenic purpura, Guillain-Barne syndrome. Allogenic bone marrow transplantation.', 'Hypersensitivity, IgA-deficient patients.', 'Increased risk of ARF in patients with renal impairment, DM, hypovolaemia, overweight, concomitant nephrotoxic medicianl products or >65 year. Pregnancy and lactation.', 'Headache, hyperthermia, nausea, vomiting, abdominal pain, fatique, dizziness, myalgia, hypotension and tachycardia. Allergic cuyaneous reactions.'),
(688, 'Sulfamoxole', 'Sulphamethoxazole bacteriostatic antibiotic more oftenly used in combination with trimethoprim. Infections caused by - Streptococcus, Staphylococcus Aureus, E coli, H.Influenzae, Anaerobes, Salmonella, Toxoplasmosis, Nocardiasis, toxoplasmosis.', 'Hypersensitivity.', 'Hybration should be adequate.', 'GI upset. Anaphylaxis. Skin rashes. Neutropenia. Thrombocytopenia. Crystalluria.'),
(689, 'Sitagliptin', 'Type II Diabetis Mellitus.', 'Diabetic ketoacidosis, Renal Impairment. Type I Diabetis Mellitus. Hypersensitivity. Pregnancy and lactation.', 'Watch for development of hypoglycemia.', 'Headache. Upper respiratory tract infection. GI  disturbances. Rarely convulsions, ataxia, slurred speech. Emotional instability.'),
(690, 'Gentamicin', 'Severe infections caused by susceptible gm negative organisms eg - Billary tract infections, Brucellosis, Cat scratch disease, Cystic fibrosis, endocarditis, endometritis, gastroenteritis, granuloma inguinale, listeriosis, meningitis, otitis externa, pelvic inflammatory disease, peritonitis, plaque, pneumonia, septicaemia, skin infections, UTI.', 'Uraemia, severe renal function impairment, pregnancy, neonates. Hypersensitivity. Pregnancy. Perforated ear drum.', 'Dose of gentamicin must be precisely calculated according to body weight and level of renal function. If irritation persists, discontinue the treatment. Do not touch the dropper as it may contaminate the solution. Use within one month of opening the container. Do not use if fungal, viral, tuberculous or purulent conditions prevail. Perforated ear drum. Concurrent use of neuromuscular blocking agents, myasthenia gravis, parkinsonism, conditions predisposing to ototoxicity and nephrotoxicity. Lactation. Monitor auditory and renal functions.', 'Irreversible ototoxicity, nephrotoxicity, headache, rashes, thrombocytopenia and joint pain. Transient irritation.'),
(691, 'Vasopressin', 'Pituitary diabetes insipidus, bleeding from oesophageal varices.', 'Hypersensitivity. Chronic nephritis. Coronary artery disease.', 'Heart failure, migraine, epilepsy, asthma or other conditions. Fluid retention, renal impairment. HTN.', 'Pallor, nausea, belching, abdominal cramps, desire to defacate, hypersensitivity reactions, constriction of coronary arteries (may cause anginal attacks and myocardial ischaemia). Tremor, vertigo, fluid retention, hyponatraemia, gangrene, arrhythmias, bradycardia, bronchoconstriction.'),
(692, 'Oxyphenbutazone', 'Weak analgesic and antipyretic action.', 'Hypersensitivity. Existing bone marrow depression. Gastric and/or duodenal ulcer. Renal impairment.', 'Pregnancy, lactation, children and elderly.', 'Gastric irritation and ulceration, oedema, hypersensitivity, hypothyroid, bone marrow depression.'),
(693, 'Sisomycin', 'Infections caused by Pseudomonas, other gram-negative bacilli and beta haemolytic streptococci and faecal streptococci. Commonly used in chest infections and SABE.', 'Hypersensitivity. Pregnancy, lactation and children below the age of six years. Not for ophthalmic use. Myasthenia gravis.', 'Renal impairment. Not to be used along with other aminoglycosides.', 'Ototoxicity. Nephrotoxicity. CNS disturbances.'),
(694, 'Dacarbazine', 'Metastatic malignant melanoma, hodgkins disease. Soft tissue sarcomas.', 'Marrow suppression, hypersensitivity. Contraindicated during pregnancy and lactation.', 'Hematological monitoring periodically warranted. Restrict food intake 4-6 hours prior to therapy. Caution in handling as it is irritant skin and tissues. Renal and hepatic impairment.', 'Bone marrow suppression, hepatic impairment, flu like syndrome, facial flushing, rash, CNS disturbances, blurred vision, paresthesia, anorexia, nausea, vomiting, alopecia, Budd-chiari syndrome.'),
(695, 'Fenofibrate', 'Hyperlipidaemias.', 'Hypersensitivity. Severe hepatic and renal impairment. Unexplained persistent liver function abnormality and primary billary cirrhosis, preexisting gall bladder disease. Pregnancy and lactation.', 'Renal or hepatic impairment. Monitor LFTs and blood counts regularly. Increased risk of cholelithiasis, pancreatitis, skeletal muscle effects. Withdraw treatment if no adequate response after 2 month of treatment at maximum recommended dose.', 'Headache, dizziness, asthaenia, fatigue, arrhythmia, photosensitivity, eczema, dizziness, vaginitis, paraesthesia, rhinitis, cough, sinusitis, allergic pulmonary alveolitis, polyuria, myopathy, myolitis, arthralgia, myalgia, myasthenia. Hepatitis, cholecystitis.'),
(696, 'Hydroxyprogestrone Hexanoate', 'As contraceptive. Hormone replacement therapy (HRT). Dysfunctional uterine bleeding. Endrometriosis. Premenstrual syndrome/tension. Threatened/habitual abortion. Endometrial carcinoma. Dysmenorrhea. Suppression of postpartum lactation. Hypoventilation.', 'Hypersensitivity.Undiagnosed vaginal bleeding, breast cancer, pregnancy, lactation. Thromboembolic disorders. History of seizures. Markedly impaired liver functions.', 'Diabetes. Exclude pregnancy. Suspicion of thromboembolic disorders.', 'Breast engorgement, headache, rise in body temperature, edema, esophageal reflux, acne and mood swings may occur. Irregular bleeding or amenorrhoea. Long term use of progestin in HRT may increase the risk of breast cancer. Blood sugar may rise and diabetes may be precipitated by long-term use of potent agents like levonorgestrel. Given in early pregnancy, progestins can cause masculinization of female foetus and other congenital abnormalities.'),
(697, 'Pentaerythritol Tetranitrate', 'Angina pectoris.', 'Severe hypotension, heart failure, marked anaemia, hypertrophic obstructive cardiomyopathy, ptients with cerebral haemorrhage or head trauma, low cardiac output secondary to hypovolaemia, inferior MI with right ventricular involvement, raised intracranial pressure. Hypothyroidism.', 'Severe hepatic or renal impairment. Malnutrition, hypothermia, gluacoma, mitral valve prolapse, cardiac tamponade. Pregnancy and lactation.', 'Flushing of the face, dizziness, tachycardia, throbbing headache and tolerance. Abdominal pain, apprehension, weakness, vertigo. Paradoxical bradycardia.'),
(698, 'Letrozole', 'Advanced breast cancer in postmenopausal women, pre-operative treatment in post-menopausal women with localised hormone-receptor-positive breast cancer (to allow subsequent breast conserving surgery).', 'Severe hepatic and renal impairment; premenopausal women. Pregnancy and lactation. Osteoporosis.', 'Severe renal impairment.', 'Diarrhoea, abdominal pain, anorexia or weight gain, dyspnoea, chest pain, dizziness, rash, pruritus, vomiting, dyspepsia, constipation, hot flushes, nausea, osteoporosis, musculoskeletal pain, vag irritation. Thromboembolic events.'),
(699, 'Dactinomycin (Actinomycin D)', 'Wilms tumour, rhabdomyosarcoma, carcinoma of testis and uterus.', 'Infection with chicken pox or herpes zoster. Hypersensitivity. Contraindicated during pregnancy and lactation.', 'Exercise caution when administering within two months of irradiation for the treatment of right sided wilms tumour. Discontinue the administration of drug if stomatitis, diarrhoea or severe hemopoietic depression results.', 'Dysphagia, esophagitis, ulcerative stomatitis, pharyngitis, anorexia, nausea, vomiting, abdominal pain, diarrhoea, GIT ulceration, liver toxicity including ascites, hepatomegaly, hepatitis, liver function test abnormalities, anaemia, agranulocytosis, leukopenia, thrombopenia, pancytopenia, reticulopenia, alopecia, skin eruptions, acne, flare-up of erythema or increased pigmentation of previously irradiated skin. Malaise, fatique, lethargy, fever, myalgia, proctitis and hypocalcaemia.'),
