(758, 'Estramustine', 'Carcinoma of the prostate, especially in cases unresponsive to or relapsing after treatment by conventional oestrogens therapy or by orchidectomy.', 'The use of estramustine is contraindicated in patients with peptic ulceration, or those with severe liver dysfunction or myocardial insufficiency, use in children and in patients hypersensitive to oestradiol or nitrogen mustard.', 'Use with caution in patients with moderate to severe bone marrow depression, thrombophlebitis, thrombosis, thromboembolic disorders, cardiovascular disease, coronary artery disease and congestive heart failure. Caution should also be exercised in patients with diabetes, hypertension, epilepsy, hepatic and renal impairment and disease associated with hypercalcaemia. Patients with prostate cancer and osteoblastic metastases are at risk of hypocalcaemia and should have calcium levels closely monitored.', 'The most common adverse effects include gynoecomastia and impotence, nausea/vomiting and fluid retention/oedema. The most serious reactions are thromboembolism, ischaemic heart disease, congestive heart failure and rarely angioneurotic oedema.'),
(759, 'Kanamycin', 'Antimicrobial spectrum of streptoycin is relatively narrow, active primarily against aerobic gram-negative bacilli, but potency is low. Sensitivie organisms are - H.ducreyi, Brucella, Yersinia pestis, Francisella tularensis, Nocardia, Calym, granulomatis, M.tuberculosis, Only few strains of E.coli, H.influenzae, V.cholerae, Shigella, Klebsiella, entero-cocci and some gram-positive cocci. Due to high incidence of toxicity both to cochlea and kidney it is now occasionally used only as a second line drug in resistant tuberculosis.', 'Hypersensitivity. Pregnancy and lactation. Renal impairment.', 'Parkinsonism, myasthenia gravis. Should not be interacted with neuromuscular blocking drugs, anaesthetics, frusemide, ethacrynic acid. Control blood levels and total dosage in patients with renal impairment. Infants, neonates and elderly.', 'Irreversible hearing loss, toxic to kidney. Neuromuscular blockade.'),
(760, 'Diclofenac Diethylammonium', 'Rheumatoid arthritis, osteoarthritis, low back pain, ankylosing spondylitis, gout. Acute musculo skeletal disorders, periarthritis (Frozen shoulder) tendinitis, tenosynovitis, bursitis, sprains and dislocations. Painful post-operative conditions. Pain following dental surgery. Painful inflammatory conditions in gynaecology. Inhibition of intraoperative miosis and postoperative inflammation in cataract surgery.', 'Soft contact lenses, aspirin/anti inflammatory drug induced allergy. Active or recurrent peptic ulcers, hypersensitivity, asthmatic patients in whom attacks of asthma are precipitated by aspirin or other NSAIDs. Treatment of perioperative pain in CABG surgery. 3rd trimester of pregnancy. < Contraindicated during pregnancy and lactation. Contraindicated to paediatrics.', 'Patients having a history of GI ulceration, haematemesis or melaena, ulcerative colitis. Crohns disease, cardiac and renal insufficiency, elderly patients. Bleeding disorder and patients on anticoagulants therapy.', 'Burning, stinging, delayed healing, GI upset, burning sensation, blurred vision, photosensitivity and keratitis punctate. Epigastric pain, nausea, diarrhoea, tiredness, insomnia, skin rash, itching, retention of fluid. Hypersensitivity. Stevens-Johnson syndrome, exfoliative dermatitis, toxic epidermal necrolysis.'),
(761, 'Prednicarbate', 'Atopic eczema. Allergic contact dermatitis. Lichen simplex. Primary irritant dermatitis. Seborrheic dermatitis. Psoriasis of face, flexures. Varicose eczema. Cystic acne. Alopecia areata. Discoid LE. Hypertrophied scars, keloids. Lichen planus. Nail disorders. Psoriasis of palm, sole, elbow, knee. A combination of steroid with proper antibiotic cover may also be used for: Impetigo, furunculosis, secondary infected dermatoses, napkin rash, otitis externa, intertriginous eruptions.', 'Hypersensitivity. Rosacea or perioral dermatitis. Primary infective skin. Pregnancy and lactation.', 'Infants. Secondary dermatological infections.', 'Thinning of epidermis. Dermal changes - atrophy. Telangiectasia, Striae. Easy bruising, Hypopigmentation. Delayed wound healing. Fungal and bacterial infections. Systemic adverse effects of topical steroids on prolong use: Adrenal pituitary suppression. Cushings syndrome.'),
(762, 'Auranofin', 'Active progressive rheumatoid arthritis.', 'Severe blood dyscrasias. Progressive renal disease. Severe hepatic disorder, SLE. History of necrotising enterocolitis, pulmonary fibrosis, exfoliative dermatitis, bone marrow aplasia. Contraindicated during pregnancy and lactation. Contraindicated to paediatrics.', 'Periodically monitor blood counts and urinary protein. Women of child bearing age should use effective contraception during and at least six months after treatment. Renal and hepatic dysfunction. History of bone marrow depression.', 'Diarrhoea, nausea, abdominal pain, ulcerative enterocolitis, rashes, pruritus, alopecia, blood dyscrasias, taste disturbance, pulmonary fibrosis, nephrotic syndrome.'),
(763, 'Atracurium Besilate', 'Medium acting non-depolarising muscle relaxation in surgical anaesthesia.', 'Depressed respiration, inadequate general anaesthesia. Hypersensitivity. Contraindicated during pregnancy.', 'Myasthenia gravis. Myopathy. Depolarising drugs, Poliomyelitis. Severe cardiovascular disease. Severe obesity. Renal insufficiency. Hypertension. Hepatic disease, electrolyte disturbances.', 'Bronchospasm, flushing, hypotension.'),
(764, 'Succinyl Choline Chloride', 'Anaesthesia for brief procedures, e.g. endotracheal intubation, laryngoscopy, bronchoscopy, esophagoscopy, reduction of fractures, dislocations, and to treat laryngospasm. Assisted ventilation. Severe cases of tetanus and status epilepticus.', 'Myasthenia gravis. Hyperkalaemia. Glaucoma. Premature infants and new borns.', 'Younger children.', 'Muscle fasciculations and soreness, changes in BP and heart rate, arrhythmias. Hyperkalaemia.'),
(765, 'Goserelin', 'Palliative treatment of prostatic carcinoma.', 'Hypersensitivity. Pregnancy and lactation.', 'Urinary tract obstruction or spinal cord compression.', 'Headache, emotional lability, depression, insomnia, diaphoresis, dizziness, breast swelling/tenderness, inj site reactions. Anaphylaxis.'),
(766, 'Enoxaparin', 'Prevention of deep vein thrombosis.Risk reduction for pulmonary embolism secondary thrombus formation during haemodialysis. Prophylaxis of VTE during surgical procedures. Unstable angina.', 'Hypersensitivity, acute septic endocarditis, hemorrhagic stroke, peptic ulcer history of thrombocytopenia.', 'Haemorrhage, thromocytopenia, local reactions. Renal or hepatic impairment, history of GI ulceration, uncontrolled hypertension, spinal or epidural anaesthesia, lactation and pregnancy, elderly. Periodic blood counts, platelet count and stool occult blood test recommended.', 'Hepatic insufficiency, peptic ulcer, arterial hypertension, diabetic nephropathy, spinal anaesthesia and epidural block pregnancy and lactations. Do not administer I.M. Thrombocytopenia, mild bleeding, Inj site irritation, pain and ecchymoses, hypersensitivity and erythema. Haemorrhagic complications.'),
(767, 'Oestriol', 'Menopause (Hormone replacement therapy). Oral contraception. Threatened or habitual abortion. Dysmenorrhea. Dysfunctional uterine bleeding. Failure of ovarian development Hirsuitism. Senile osteoporosis. Post menopausal osteoporosis. Breast cancer. Prostatic carcinoma. Suppression of post partum lactation. Senile vaginitis. Delayed puberty in girls. Acne (Not usually given).', 'Pregnancy. Thromboembolic disorders, coronary and cerebrovascular diseases or a history of it.. Moderate-to-severe hypoertension, hyperlipidaemia. Active liver disease, hepatoma or history of jaundice during past pregnancy. Suspected.overt malignancy of genitals/breast. Prophyria. Impending major surgery - avoid post-operative thromboembolism.', 'Diabetes: control may be vitiated. Obesity. Smoking. Undiagnosed vaginal bleeding. Uterine leiomyoma: may enlarge with estrogenic preparations, progestin only pills can be used. Mentally ill. Age above 35 years. Mild hypertension. Migraine. Gallbladder disease.', 'Thromboembolic disorders. Coronary and cerebral thrombosis. Rising BP. Lipid disorders. Genital carcinoma. Benign hepatoma. Gall stones. Weight gain. Chloasma. Pruritus Vulvae. DM. Emotional instability. Nausea, Vomiting, headache, breath through bleeding, breast discomfort. Suppression of libido, gynaecomastia and feminization when given to males. Fusion of epiphyses and reduction of adult stature when given to children. Stilbestrol given to pregnancy women, especially during first trimester increases the incidence of vaginal and cervical carcinoma in female off spring. In postmenopausal women, estrogens can increase the risk of irregular bleeding and endometrial carcinoma. Estrogens can accelerate the growth of existing breast cancer. Migraine, epilepsy and endometriosis may be worsened by estrogens.'),
(768, 'Folic Acid lP', 'Folate-deficient. Megaloblastic anaemia. Prophylaxis of megaloblastic anemia in pregnancy. Prophylaxis of neural tube defect in pregnancy. Malabsorption syndromes. Antiepileptic therapy.', 'Undiagnosed, megaloblastic anaemia, pernicious, aplastic or normocytic anaemias.', 'Treatment resistance may occur in patients with depressed haematopoiesis, alcoholism, deficiencies of other vitamins. Neonates.', 'Rarely hypersensitivity.'),
(769, 'Bupropion', 'Treatment of nocotine dependence as an aid to smoking cessation.', 'Hypersensitivity. Seizure disorder, bulimia or anorexia nervosa, monoamine oxidase inhibitors. Contraindicated during pregnancy and lactation.', 'The recommended dose should not be exceeded. Renal impairment. It may precipitate a manic episode in patients with bipolar disorder during the depressed phase of there illness and may activate latent psychosis in other susceptible patients. Concomitant therapy with drugs predominantly metabolised by this isoenzyme (such as certain beta-blockers, antiarrhythmics, SSRIS, TCAs, Antisychotics) should be initiated at the lower end of the dose range. It may affect ability to perform tasks that require judgment or motor and congnitive skills.', 'Fever, chest pain, asthenia, tachycardia, vasodilation, postural hypotension, increased blood pressure (in some case severe), flushing, syncope, seizures, insomnia, tremor, concentration disturbance, headache, dizziness, depression, confusion, agitation, anxiety, irritability, hostility, anorexia, dry mouth, gastrointestinal disturbance including nausea and vomiting, abdominal painm constipation. Rash, pruritus and sweating.'),
(770, 'Difluprednate', 'Replacement therapy: Adrenal insufficiency. Adrenogenital syndrome. Nonendocrine diseases: Rheumatoid arthirits. Osteoarthritis, Acute gouty arthirits. Collagen diseases e.g. systemic lupus erythematosus, polyarteritis nodosa, dermatomyositis, nephritic syndrome, glomerulonephritis and related diseases. Severe allergic reactions e.g. anaphylaxis, angioneurotic edema, urticaria and serum sickness and related diseases. Autoimmune diseases e.g. haemolytic anaemia, idiopathic thrombocytopenic purpura, active chronic hepatitis and related diseases. Other lung diseases e.g. pulmonary edema, accelerate lung maturation and surfactant production in the foetus and prevent respiratory distress syndrome at birth. Infective diseases e.g. severe forms of tuberculosis, severe lepra reaction, certain forms of bacterial meningitis and Pneumocystis carinii pneumonia with hypoxia in AIDS patients along with proper antibiotic cover. Eye diseases e.g. inflammatory ocular diseases, allergic conjunctivitis, iritis, iridocyclitis, keratitis, retinitis, optic neuritis, uveitis. Skin diseases e.g. eczematous skin diseases. Pemphigus vulgaris, exfoliative dermatitis, Stevens Johnson syndrome. Intestinal diseases e.g. ulcerative colitis, Crohns disease, coeliac disease are chronic inflammatory intestinal diseases. Cerebral edema. Malignancies e.g. Acute lymphatic leukaemia, Hodgkins and other lymphomas. Hormone responsive breast carcinoma. Organ transplantation and skin allograft. Septic shock. Thyroid storm.', 'Viral, fungal, tuberculous or purulent infections unless until treated with proper antibiotic concurrently. Pregnancy. New born babies, premature infants or children below the age of five years. Peptic ulcer. Psychosis. Epilepsy. Renal failure. Osteoporosis. In ophthalmology, herps zoster, herpetic or fungal xeratitis, previous history of cataract.', 'Prolong use. CHF, hypertension, DM. Elderly and lactation.', 'Cushings habitus. Peptic ulceration may be aggravated. Sodium and fluid retention. Potassium and Calcium depletion. Muscle wasting, osteoporosis. GI disturbances and bleeding. Increased appetite and delayed wound healing. Bruising, striae, hirsutism, acne, flushing. Headache, depression, psychosis, menstrual irregularity. Suppression of pitutary-adrenocortical system. Dermal atrophy. Hyperglycaemia. Susceptibility to infection. Osteoporosis. Growth retardation. Foetal abnormalities. Topical application to the eye can produce corneal ulcers, raised IOP, reduced visual function and posterior subcapsular cataract.'),
(771, 'Zopiclone', 'Short term treatment of insomnia, including difficulty in failing asleep, nocturnal awakening and early awakening, transient situational or chronic insomnia and insomnia secondary to psychiatric disturbances.', 'Hypersenstivity. Hepatic impairment. Decompensated respiratory insufficiency. Myasthenia gravis. Severe sleep apnoea. Pregnancy, lactation and children.', 'Alcoholism. Renal insufficiency. May impair ability to drive or operate machinery.', 'Metalic taste. GI disturbances. Urticaria. Irritability, confusion, depressed mood, aggressiveness and incoordination.'),
(772, 'Cefaclor', 'Infections due to sensitive Gram-positive and Gram-negative bacteria', 'Cephalosporin hypersensitivity.', 'In penicillin sensitive patients, chronic renal failure. Pseudomembranous colities, infants less than 1 month.', 'Hypersensitivity reactions, diarrhoea, nausea, vomiting, transient hepatitis, eosinophilia, genital pruritus or vaginitis, reversible interstitial nephritis.'),
(773, 'Indinavir', 'Treatment of HIV infection in combination with antiretroviral agents.', 'Hypersensitivity. Avoid concurrent use with terfenadine, cisapride, astemizole, triazolam, midazolam or ergot derivatives. Pregnancy and lactation. Severe hepatic impairment.', 'Hyperglycaemia. Increased risk of urolithiasis/nephrolithiasis. Hyperbilirubinaemia may be exacerbated. Diabetes haemophilia.', 'Nausea, vomiting, diarrhoea, abdominal discomfort, dry mouth, taste disturbances, headache, dizziness, insomnia, myalgia, asthenia, paraesthesia, rash, pruritus, dry skin, hyperpigmentation, nephrolithiasis (may require interruption or discontinuation), dysuria, haematuria, crystalluria, proteinuria, elevated liver enzymes and bilirubin, hepatitis, blood disorders including neutropenia, haemolytic anaemia, hyperglycaemia.');
INSERT INTO `patientModule` (`Id`, `DrugName`, `Indication`, `ContraIndication`, `Caution`, `SideEffects`) VALUES
(774, 'Fluocinolone Acetonide', 'Atopic eczema. Allergic contact dermatitis. Lichen simplex. Primary irritant dermatitis. Seborrheic dermatitis. Psoriasis of face, flexures. Varicose eczema. Cystic acne. Alopecia areata. Discoid LE. Hypertrophied scars, keloids. Lichen planus. Nail disorders. Psoriasis of palm, sole, elbow, knee. A combination of steroid with proper antibiotic cover may also be used for: Impetigo, furunculosis, secondary infected dermatoses, napkin rash, otitis externa, intertriginous eruptions.', 'Hypersensitivity. Rosacea or perioral dermatitis. Primary infective skin. Pregnancy and lactation.', 'Infants. Secondary dermatological infections.', 'Thinning of epidermis. Dermal changes - atrophy. Telangiectasia, Striae. Easy bruising, Hypopigmentation. Delayed wound healing. Fungal and bacterial infections. Systemic adverse effects of topical steroids on prolong use: Adrenal pituitary suppression. Cushings syndrome.'),
(775, 'Etidronate Disodium', 'Pagets disease of bone. Prevention and treatment of ectopic ossification complicating hip replacement. Osteoporosis in postmenopausal women. Hypercalcaemia of malignancy.', 'Osteoporosis with hypercalcaemia/hypercalciuria, osteomalacia.', 'In pagets disease, ensure 90 day drug-free interval between treatment courses, renal disease, children, malnutrition, patients with fracture (especially of long bones). May exacerbate asthma in asthmatics. Pregnancy and lactation.', 'GI symtoms like abdominal pain, constipation, diarrhoea and nausea. Recurrent bone pain at pagetic sites or the onset of pain at previously asymptomatic sites, metallic, altered or loss of taste during or shortly after the treatment. Headache, paraesthesia, leucopenia, agranulocytosis.'),
(776, 'Cyproheptadine', 'Loss of appetite, allergy and pruritis, in migraine and vascular headache.', 'Prostatic hypertrophy.', 'Pregnancy', 'Drowsiness, dry mouth, confusion, ataxia, weight gain.'),
(777, 'Nandrolone', 'Synthetic androgens with higher anabolic and lower androgenic activity. Catabolic states. Renal insufficiency. Osteoporosis. Suboptimal growth in boys. Hypoplastic, haemolytic and malignancy associated anaemia. To enhance physical ability in atheletes. Metastatic breast cancer.', 'Prostatic or breast carcinoma (male). Liver disease, nephrosis, porphyria. Infants, pregnancy and lactation. Patients who may be adversely affected by fluid retention - such as CHF, epilepsy, migraine.', 'Diabetic patients. Hepatic impairment. Elderly. Discontinue if signs of virilisation in women occur.', 'Male: Postpuberal, Acne, gyanecomastia, bladder, irritability, priapism, insomnia, chills, decreased libido, hepatic dysfunction, nausea, diarrhoea, prostatic hyperplasia. Acne, virilism, chills, insomnia, hyperpigmentation, diarrhoea, nausea. Female, Virilism, hypercalcaemia, nausea, diarrhoea, chills, insomnia, Iron deficiency anaemia, hepatic dysfunction. OXYMETHOLONE, STANOZOLOL CAN PRODUCE JAUNDICE AND WORSEN LIPID PROFILE.'),
(778, 'Flunisolide', 'Asthma and allergic rhinitis.', 'Untreated fungal, bacterial or viral infections of the nose or eyes. Hypersensitivity. First trimester during pregnancy.', 'Congestive heart failure, recent myocardial infarction, hypertension, diabetes mellitus, epilepsy, glaucoma, hypothyroidism, osteoporosis, peptic ulceration, psychoses, renal or hepatic impairment, elderly, children, pregnancy and lactation.', 'Taste disturbance. Mild transient nasal burning and stinging.'),
(779, 'Perindopril (Perindopril Erbumine)', 'Hypertension. Heart failure. Stable coronary artery disease.', 'Unstable coronary artery disease. Hypovolaemia or hyponatraemia. Children, pregnancy and lactation. Renal failure. Hypersensitivity. Potassium sparing diuretic.', 'Hepatic impairment. Collagen vascular disease. Unilateral renal artery stenosis and pre-existing renal insufficiency.  Valvular aortic stenosis. Before, during or immediately after anaesthesia.  Hypotension if drug is being administered along with diueretics.', 'Headache, cough, fatigue, dizziness, sleep disorders, depression, fever, nervousness, somnolence, cough, abnormal ECG, palpitation, rash, hyperkalaemia, elevated triglycerides, menstrual disorder, nausea, vomiting, dyspepsia. Mood disturbance, insomnia, abdominal pain and taste impairment. Hypersensitivity.'),
(780, 'Bendamustine', 'Chronic lymphocytic leuakemia, lymphoma (NHL), sarcoma (under study).', 'Hypersensitivity. Pregnancy and lactation. Smoking.', 'Renal and heapatic diseases.', 'Nausea, vomiting, fatigue, diarrhoea, fever, loss of appetite, cough, headache. Weight loss. Rashes. Difficulty in breathing. Bone marrow and immunosuppression.'),
(781, 'Fluconazole', 'Superficial mucosal candidiasis. Candidal balanitis, vaginal candidiasis. Dermatophytosis, pityriasis, versicolor and candida infections. Cryptococcal infections including meningitis, systemic candidasis. Prevention of relapse following a primary course of antifungal treatment for acute cryptococcal infections in patients with aids. Prophylaxis of fungal infections in immunocompromised patients.', 'Hypersensitivity.', 'Renal or hepatic impairment. May prolong QT interval. Pregnancy and lactation.', 'Nausea, headache, skin rash, abdominal pain, vomiting and diarrhoea. Elevated liver function values, rash, exfoliative. Rarely angioedema, anaphylactic reactions and thrombocytopenia. Hepatotoxicity, rarely anaphylaxis. Stevens-Johnson syndrome.'),
(782, 'Sodium Fusidate', 'Skin infections caused by staphylococci, Streptococci, Corynebacterium minutissimu, propionobacterium, acnes and other organism sensitive to Fusidic acid.', 'Hypersensitivity, severe hepatic failure. Contraindicated during lactation.', 'Neonates and pregnancy.', 'Jaundice and liver dysfunction (reversible), GI disturbances, IV venospasm, haemolysis, hypocalcaemia, SC/IM. Tissue necrosis. Topical: Rashes and irritation.'),
(783, 'Glucagon', 'Hypoglycaemia. Cardiogenic. Diagnosis of Pheochromocytoma', 'Phaeochromocytoma, hypersensitivity.', 'Ineffective in chronic hypoglycaemia, alcohol induced hypoglycaemia, starvation and adrenal insufficiency, diagnostic aid in diabetic patients or in elderly with heart disease. Insulinoma, glucagonoma. Pregnancy.', 'Nausea, vomiting, diarrhoea. Hypokalaemia.'),
(784, 'Nebivolol', 'Essential hypertension. Adjunct in the treatment of stable chronic heart failure.', 'Hepatic impairment, sick sinus syndrome, 2nd and 3rd degree heart block (without a packmaker), history of asthma, metabolic acidosis, severe peripheral arterial disease, severe bradycardia, cardiogenic shock or decompensated heart failure, untreated phaeochromocytoma. Pregnancy and lactation.', 'Elderly. History of anaphylaxis to various allergens, 1st degree AV block, peripheral arterial disease, DM, compensated heart failure, myasthenia gravis, history of psychiatric illness, renal impairment. May mask signs of hyperthyroidism (e.g. tachycardia).', 'Peripheral oedema, bradycardia, chest pain, headache, fatigue, dizziness, insomnia, rash, hypercholesterolaemia, decreased HDL levels, hyperuricaemia, increased TG levels, increased uric acid levels, diarrhoea, nausea, abdominal pain, thrombocytopenia, paraesthesia, weakness, increased BUN, dyspnoea. Anaphylaxis.'),
(785, 'Testosterone Propionate', 'Testicular failure. Hypopituitarism. AIDS related muscle wasting. Hereditary angioneurotic edema. Ageing.', 'Hypersensitivity. Prostate and male breast carcinoma. Pregnancy and lactation. Hypercalcaemia or hypercalciuria.', 'Cardiovascular disorders, skeletal metastases, renal or hepatic impairment, epilepsy, migraine, diabetes. Elderly, prepubertal boys.', 'Virilization, excess body hair and menstrual irregularities in women. Acne. Frequent, sustained and often painful erections in males in the beginning of therapy, subside spontaneously after sometime. Oligozoospermia. Precocious puberty and shortening of stature. Edema. Cholestatic jaundice. Hepatic carcinoma. Gynaecomastia. Lowering of HDL and rise in LDL levels.'),
(786, 'Ceftizoxime', 'Aerobic gram-negative as well as some gram positive bacteria. B.fragilis. Meningitis by gram-negative bacilli, life threating resistant/hospital-acquired infections, septicaemias. Infections in immunocompromised patients.', 'Hypersensitivity. Cephalosporins, hyperbilirubinaemic neonates.', 'Renal impairment. History of penicillin allergy. Pregnancy and lactation.', 'GI disturbances, candidiasis, eosinophilia, neutropenia, leucopenia, thrombo-cytopenia, rise in liver enzymes and blood urea. Superinfection, diarrhoea, Pseudomembranous colitis.'),
(787, 'Miglitol', 'In the management of type II diabetes mellitus alone or with a sulfonylurea.', 'Hypersensitivity. Renal impairment. GI motility disorders or inflammtory bowel disease. Diabetic ketoacidosis. Partial intestinal obstruction.', 'Hypoglycaemia.', 'Abdominal pain, diarrhoea, flatulence, skin rash.'),
(788, 'Bemiparin Sodium', 'Venous thromboembolism. Prophylaxis of postoperative VTE including during pregnancy with a history of deep-vein thrombosis or pulmonary embolism. Prevention of mural thrombosis. Acute peripheral arterial embolism, unstable angina. Venous thromboembolism.', 'Bleeding disorders, thrombocytopenia, severe hypotension, threatened abortion, piles, G.I. ulcers. Sub acute bacterial endocarditis, large malignancies, tuberculosis. Ocular and neurosurgery, lumbar puncture. Chronic alcoholics. Aspirin and other anti platelet drugs. Do not apply to bleeding areas or eyes. Patch test for tolerance before use on chronic open lesions. Severe renal and hepatic impairment. Cerebral or subarachnoid haemorrhage.', 'Renal or hepatic impairment. Not for systemic use or application to mucus membranes. Discontinue treatment if thrombocytopenia occurs. Hypersensitivity, elderly.', 'Bleeding due to overdose. Transient and reversible alopecia. Osteoporosis. Hypersensitivity reactions include urticaria, conjunctivitis, rhinitis, asthma, angioedema and anaphylactic shock, priapism. Bleeding, rash, aching bones, thrombocytopenia, alopecia, anaphylaxis, rigor, slight haematuria.'),
(789, 'Paclitaxel', 'Ovarian carcinoma. Breast Cancer. Advanced non-smell cell lung cancer. AIDS related Kaposis sarcoma.', 'Hypersensitivity. Pregnancy, lactation and children. concurrent serious uncontrolled infections.', 'Bone marrow suppression during therapy.', 'Bone marrow depression, hypersensitivity reactions, myalgia, chest pain, bradycardia, a stocking-glove sensory neuropathy, mucositis, nausea, vomiting, diarrhoea, alopeia. Tachycardia, rash, hypotension, arthralgia, rarely hepatic necrosis and encephalopathy.'),
(790, 'Iron III Hydroxy Polymaltose', 'Iron deficiency either due to chronic blood loss or poor absorption.', 'Iron intolerance.', 'History peptic ulcer, severe renal failure. Iron and tetracycline bind together leading to impairment of absorption.', 'GI upset, black stools, abdominal discomfort or pain by oral therapy.'),
(791, 'Calcium Fluoride', 'Calcium supplements are usually required where dietary calcium intake is deficient. This dietary requirement varies with age and is relatively greater in childhood, pregnancy and lactation due to an increased demand. Calcium supplement is also required in paused menopausal women and persons with osteopenia specially after the age of 60 years.', 'Patients with Calculi renal calculi or history of renal calculi; hypercalcaemia; hypophosphataemia.', 'Renal impairment, hypercalcaemia-associated disease eg. other malignancies; sarcoidosis; elderly.', 'Co-administration with thiazide diuretics or Vit D may lead to milk alkali syndrome and hypercalcaemia. Decreased absorption with coricosteroids. Decreases absorption of tetracyclinea, atenolol, iron, quinolones, alendronate, Na fluoride, Zn and calcium-channel blockers. Enhances cardiac effects of digitialis glycosides and may precipitate digitalis intoxication.'),
(792, 'Albuterol Sulphate', 'Reversible airways obstruction. Premature labour.', 'Cardiovascular disease. Eclampsia and severe pre-eclampsia, intra-uterine infection, intra-uterine foetal death, antepartum haemorrhage, placenta praevia and cord compression, threatened miscarriage, cardiac disease.', 'Hypertensive ischaemic heart disease. Receiving digitalis.', 'Arrythmias. Tremors, Palpitation, restlessness, nervousness, throat irritation and ankle edema. Tremor, muscle cramps, headache, hypokalaemia.'),
(793, 'Mitoxantrone', 'Acute non-lymphocytic leukaemia. Carcinoma of breast. Non-Hodgkins lymphoma. Chronic myelogenous leukaemia.', 'Myelosuppression. Severe cardiac, hepatic or renal disfunction. Multiple sclerosis. Pregnancy, lactation and children.', 'Prior radiotherapy or anthracycline therapy. Concomitant cytotoxic therapy.', 'Dyspnoea, arrhythmia, oedema, ECG , fatigue, fever, headache, alopecia, nail bed changes, amenorrhoea, hyperglycaemia, anorexia, bleeding, mucositis, stomatitis, dyspepsia, fungal infection. Myelosuppression, cardiotoxicity.'),
(794, 'Pyrantel Pamoate', 'Single or mixed infections due to susceptible worms. Ascariasia. Necatoriasis. Enterobiasis. Trichinosis.', 'Hypersensitivity Pregnancy, lactation and children below the age of one year.', 'Liver dysfunction. Severe malnutrition.', 'Anorexia, nausea, vomiting, abdominal cramps, drowsiness, insomnia, diarrhoea, dizziness, rash.'),
(795, 'Ropinirole', 'Parkinsons disease. Restless leg syndrome.', 'Hypersensitivity. Lactation.', 'Pregnancy.', 'Dyskinesia, othostatic hypotension, nausea, dizziness, somnolence, dyspepsia, hallucinations, constipation, asthenia. May cause daytime sleepiness or episodes of falling asleep during activities. May cause or worsen pre-existing dyskinesia.'),
(796, 'Levofloxacin', 'Acute sinusitis. Acute exacerbation of chronic bronchitis. Community acquired pneumonia. Urinary tract infections including pyelonephritis. Skin and soft tissue infections.', 'Hypersensitivity. Epilepsy, history of tendon disorders in children or growing adolescents.', 'Clostridium difficile associated diseases, tendinitis. Patients predisposed to seizures. Patients with renal impairment. Prevention of photosensitisation. History of prolonged QT interval, uncorrected electrolyte disturbances. Pregnancy, lactation and elderly.', 'Nausea, diarrhoea, constipation, headache, insomnia, inj site reactions (IV). Ophthalmic transient decrease in vision, ocular burning, ocular pain or sensation, headache, fever , pharyngitis, photophobia. Anaphylaxis.'),
(797, 'Cyclophosphamide', 'Leukaemias, Lymphogranulomatosis, Lymphosarcoma, Reticulum cell sarcoma. Hodgkins disease, multiple Myeloma. Inoperable solid malignancies. Combination with surgery, radiation and other cytotroxic drugs.', 'Acute urinary tract infection. Pregnancy. Bladder haemorrhage. Myelosuppression. Lactation.', 'Chloramphenicol retards the metabolism of cyclophosphamide. Elderly debilitated. Diabetes. Discontinue if WBC. Count is less than 3000. Cardiac, hepatic or renal disease.', 'Alopecia, gonadal suppression, cardiotoxicity, pulmonary fibrosis.'),
(798, 'Aprotinin', 'Reduction of perioperative blood loss in open heart surgery, management of traumatic haemorrhagic, pancreatogenic and endotoxic shock, acute pancreatitis.', 'Hypersensitivity. Lactation.', 'Neonates and children, first trimester of pregnancy.', 'Thrombophlebitis. Hypersensitivity or pseudo-allergic reactions after first dose or thereafter.'),
(799, 'Calcipotriol', 'Topical treatment of psoriasis.', 'Hypersensitivity.', 'Not to be applied on the face: pregnancy and lactation.', 'Skin irritation, erythema, scaling, hypercalcaemia with high doses.'),
(800, 'Neomycin', 'Orally used for bacterial diarrhoeas and dysentery. Preparation of bowel before surgery. Hepatic coma. Topically for infected wound, ulcers, burn, external ear infections, conjunctivitis.', 'Hypersensitivity. Renal impairment. Pregnancy and lactation.', 'Prolonged use can induce malabsorption syndrome with diarrhoea and steatorrhoea. It decreases absorption of digoxin, bile acid reabsorption and lowers plasma cholesterol levels. Due to marked suppression of gut flora, super infection by Candida can occur.', 'Ototoxicity and nephrotoxicity.'),
